<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Citizen Convicted of Aiding Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli Court Tuesday
convicted a German citizen of being a member of Hezbollah and
conspiring with it to attack Israel, Israeli television reported.
</P>
<P>
Steven Smyrek, 26, an Islamic convert and former German
soldier, was convicted by a Tel Aviv district court of aiding
Hezbollah and trying to pass information about Israel to it.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that Smyrek had taken pictures of public
places in Israel in a bid to help Hezbollah choose targets for
possible terror attacks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel Radio, the three-judge panel unanimously
passed the ruling and said the "prosecution proved beyond a doubt
the base for conviction."
</P>
<P>
The court, however, dismissed allegations that Smyrek was
plotting a suicide bomb attack himself in a public place in
Israel. The court will possibly deliver a sentence after hearing
arguments between the prosecution and the defense.
</P>
<P>
Smyrek was arrested in November 1997 upon arrival at the Ben
Gurion airport. He admitted that he had received training with
Hezbollah in Lebanon, but Hezbollah denied after his arrest that
Smyrek worked for it.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a war of attrition to
oust Israeli troops and their local militia South Lebanon Army
from the so-called security zone Israel carved out in south
Lebanon in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting northern Israel
from cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
