<HEADLINE> Japan to Resume Loan to Iran for Dam Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan is to resume providing for
Iran 705 billion yen (about 6 billion U.S. dollars) in
low-interest loan for building the "Karoun-4" dam in the western
province of Khuzestan.
</P>
<P>
This was released here Tuesday by Asahiso Kawamora, spokesman
of the Japanese delegation headed by Foreign Minister Masakiko
Komura, who is on a three-day visit to Iran, according to the
Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The two countries reached an agreement in early 1990s on
Japan's low-interest loan for the construction of the Karoun
hydroelectric power plant. But after paying its first portion
of 38.6 billion yen (about 336 million U.S. dollars), Tokyo
froze the loan in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The unfreezing of the loan by Japan is a result of
Komura's visit, the first in years, and is indicative of a
new attitude toward Iran, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese spokesman said the two sides had discussed
various topics on political and economic affairs in addition
to the dialog between nations advocated by moderate President
Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Kawamora said the Japanese government invited Khatami to visit
Tokyo next year and the Iranian president had accepted the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran's reforms offered the Japanese government an
incentive to visit Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Japanese minister was carrying a message from
Washington to Tehran, the spokesman said he had never been
given such a commission by the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
