<HEADLINE> 19 Iraqi Civilians Killed in U.S.-British Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen Iraqi civilians were
killed and 11 others injured on Tuesday in attacks by U.S. and
British warplanes on residential areas and civilian facilities in
northern and southern Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
At 10:35 (0635 GMT) 11 formations of U.S. and British warplanes
coming from Turkish airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace over
Neineva, Erbil and Dohuk provinces, said an Iraqi military
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The fighter jets attacked some civilian and service facilities,
residential areas as well as military sites in the region, some
of the targets are not in the no-fly zone, killing eight civilians
and injuring nine others.
</P>
<P>
At 14:07 (1007 GMT) 12 formations of U.S. and British warplanes
coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi
airspace over Basrah, Thi-Qar, Qadisiyah, Misan and Wasit
provinces, causing one injury.
</P>
<P>
They attacked a residential area in Jassan district in the
southern Iraqi province of Wasit, killing 11 residents and
injuring another.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the enemy planes and
forced them to flee to their bases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have made over 11,500 sorties over the two
no-fly zones in Iraq, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
And they have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
facilities and military sites, causing severe civilian casualties
and property damages.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led western
allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
