<HEADLINE> Security Council Meet on Western Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Tuesday reaffirmed its support for the holding of the
referendum in Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the Security
Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said that members of the
Security Council heard a briefing by Assistant Secretary-General
Hedi Annabi and considered a report by the U.N. Secretary-General
on the latest development in Western Sahara.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council took note of the progress achieved in
the implementation of the Settlement Plan for Western Sahara,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the U.N. Security Council Tuesday met
in a closed-door session to discuss the latest report by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who has reported progress made by
the United Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara
(MINURSO), but efforts are under way to build confidence in the
region.
</P>
<P>
In his written report to the Security Council Monday, Annan
said, "The resumption of the identification operation and the
initiation of the appeals process, as well as the publication of
the first part of the provisional voters list, have been
achieved."
</P>
<P>
At present, the United Nations High Commission for Refugees
(UNHCR) and MINURSO are taking steps to prepare for the
repatriation of refugees in cooperation with parties concerned,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"It is now important that confidence-building measures be
implemented promptly through the establishment of communication
facilities and visits," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, it should be recognized that delays in
solving certain issues in the identification operation, the
staggered opening of the appeals centers, compounded by
difficulties in meeting the staff requirements, have affected
parties of the timetable for the referendum process," he said.
</P>
<P>
By August 9, the military component of MINURSO stood at 230
military observers and other personnel. "Under the commend of
Major General Bernd S. Lubenik of Austria, the component continued
to monitor the ceasefire between the Royal Moroccan Army and the
Frente POLISARIO forces, which remains calm and there have been no
indications that either side intends to resume hostilities in the
near future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The much-delayed U.N.-brokered referendum in Western Sahara,
originally scheduled for January 1992, is not expected to take
place before July 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
