<HEADLINE> 32 Men Tried for Smuggling Weapons in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian state security court
on Tuesday began trial of 31 Egyptians and one Libyan charged with
smuggling and illegally acquiring arms.
</P>
<P>
After the first session of hearings in the day, the State
Security Misdemeanor Court in Alexandria, a Mediterranean port
city 220 kilometers northwest of Cairo, decided to continue the
trial on September 19, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of the men were arrested on April 26 as they tried to
cross into Egypt from Libya through the el-Salloum checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
Police said the men had concealed 49 guns, including automatic
rifles, in their bags.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen other men, who had been identified by the 13
defendants during interrogations, also stood for trial.
</P>
<P>
Six of the defendants were charged with arms smuggling, an
offense that is usually punished by life imprisonment with hard
labor.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 26 were charged with illegally acquiring weapons,
usually punished by 15 years in prison with hard labor.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the men bought the weapons from Omar al-Salmani,
a Libyan soldier who worked as a guard of a Libyan weapons depot.
Al-Salmani is reported to have been executed recently in Libya for
stealing weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
