<HEADLINE> Primakov Agrees to Head Fatherland-All Russia Bloc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov on Tuesday declared his consent to head the coordinating
council of the Fatherland-All Russia alliance in a move that would
have major implications in Russia's political landscape.
</P>
<P>
Mayor of Moscow Yuri Luzhkov is in second and Governor of
St.Petersburg Vladimir Yakovlev in third place.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov and Primakov are seen as two of the strongest potential
candidates in next year's presidential poll, although neither has
formally announced plans to run.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov's Fatherland movement recently united with the "All
Russia" movement, a powerful bloc of regional governors, and
Primakov's addition will make the coalition even stronger.
</P>
<P>
Primakov thanked the bloc leadership for the trust vested in
him and promised "to use all his strength and experience to ensure
that the coalition gains a well-deserved victory in the upcoming
parliamentary elections," the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that his decision to head the council
"does not mean that I have joined one of the parties or
movements."
</P>
<P>
That could obstruct these organizations' unification in one
election source and later impede a stable unity of Centrist forces
in the State Duma, Primakov said in a statement, adding that
"entering a particular movement is unacceptable for me
personally."
</P>
<P>
Primakov listed four major tasks ahead: the creation of a
favorable atmosphere for the new Duma's law-making activity; the
promotion of synergy between the Duma and the government; the
revision of the Constitution and the strengthening of the
statehood; and the preservation of the country's integrity in
combination with federalism.
</P>
<P>
He said the amendments to the constitution should envision a
transfer of part of the presidential powers to the government and
parliament and the institution of a vice president.
</P>
<P>
Primakov also advocates either a Constitutional amendment or a
law that would guarantee former Russian presidents complete safety
and an appropriate life, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Primakov also vowed to boost Russia's
security.
</P>
<P>
""The armed forces must be in the center of public attention,
not because we are threatening someone but because we do not want
to be threatened," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
