<HEADLINE> China Says Banning Falun Gong Aiming at Defending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador in London Ma
Zhengang said on Tuesday that the Chinese government's decision to
ban Falun Gong sect was aimed at protecting the Chinese people's
human rights and maintaining social stability.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that since the banning of the
illegal sect, the over-whelming majority of Falun Gong
practitioners have seen through the true features of this
organization and broken away from it.
</P>
<P>
China's Civil Affairs Ministry issued a decision on July 22,
banning the Research Society of Falun Dafa and the Falun Gong
organization under its control after judging them to be illegal.
Later, the Public Security Ministry issued an arrest warrant for
crime suspect Li Hongzhi, founder of Falun Gong sect.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said: "Falun Gong is neither a real Qigong sect
nor a normal religious practice, but rather a cult organization
with political motives."
</P>
<P>
He said Li Hongzhi and his Falun Gong organization, with
ulterior motives, had engaged in illegal activities, incited and
created disturbances frequently, thus severely undermining social
stability.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government's decision to ban the sect has won warm
acclamation all over the country," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador hoped the international community would
also see through the true features of Falun Gong sect, understand
and support the Chinese government's decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
