<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Asks Members to Reschedule FM Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League has asked its
members to reschedule the next foreign ministers' meeting which
had been scheduled on September 4-5, a league spokesman said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Talaat Hamid said intensive contacts are underway to set a new
date for the bi-annual meeting in Cairo, which will be chaired by
Iraq under the league's rotational system.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud Al-Faisal on Sunday asked
the league to postpone the meeting to September 13, saying that
he can only attend the meeting that day.
</P>
<P>
The move appears to underline unease felt by Saudi Arabia and
its Gulf allies to attend a meeting chaired by Iraq, which they
have been trying to punish for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based league has issued invitations to the foreign
ministers of its 22 members to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's turn to chair the meeting is bound to strike
apprehension among its bitter rivals, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia,
which have blocked Arab League proposals in support of Iraq in its
campaign to have the nearly nine-year-long U.N. economic sanctions
lifted.
</P>
<P>
If the Saudi foreign minister does not attend the meeting, his
Gulf counterparts in Kuwait, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates,
Bahrain and Oman may follow suit, sending low-level envoys to head
their delegations instead.
</P>
<P>
Such a boycott would deprive Iraq of an important diplomatic
victory and would deny President Saddam Hussein an opportunity to
make Iraq heard by other members.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League convenes regular foreign ministers' meetings in
March and September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
