<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Police Investigate Deadly Stunt Car Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- French police Tuesday continued
investigation on the deadly stunt car accident which killed a
cameraman during the shooting of the thriller "Taxi 2" in Paris on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police have questioned since Monday Remy Julienne, who was in
charge of stunt in the shooting of "Taxi 2", and the film's
conductor Gerard Krawczyk, while an autopsy of the body of Alain
Dutartre, 41, was conducted on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dutartre was killed after being hit by the stuntman's car
flying from a springboard and overshooting its target by
nosediving into a group of film crew.
</P>
<P>
Dutartre's assistant, Jean-Michel Bar, who had both his legs
broken after being hit by the stunt car, will have an operation on
Tuesday and will also be asked to give his version of the accident
as soon as his health allows, said police.
</P>
<P>
The driver of the Peugeot 406 stunt car, who is also injured in
the accident, was reduced to a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
According to the film script, the car was supposed to jump from
a springboard over three army tanks before landing on a heap of
cardboard.
</P>
<P>
The first try was not judged satisfactory, as the car, equipped
with an aerofoil, did not fly high enough and landed before
reaching the cardboard.
</P>
<P>
For an unknown reason, the car overshot on the second try and
landed 15 to 20 meters ahead of the fixed area with a speed of 100
to 120 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
The schedule to shoot the remaining part of "Taxi 2" in
Marseille has been postponed for a short period of time, said the
film producer, Luc Besson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
