<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Concerned at Conflict in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday voiced its concerns at the eruption of fighting in
Kisangani, the Democratic Republic of Congo, between troops from
Rwanda and Uganda and the Congolese rebel factions, and demanded
an immediate end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the Council,
Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said, "Members of the Council expressed
serious concern at the eruption of fighting in Kisangani,
Democratic Republic of the Congo, reportedly between troops from
Rwanda and Uganda and the Congolese rebel factions."
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the 15-nation Security Council were
briefed by the U.N. Secretariat on the situation in Congo (K),
former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The Council members "were particularly concerned that the
fighting has disrupted the national immunization days following a
request by the Secretary-General, which were supposed to provide
the opportunity for some 10 million children to be immunized
against polio, in violation of international humanitarian law,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council regretted the loss of life of innocent
civilians," the statement said. "They called upon all parties to
ensure that humanitarian agencies have access to the wounded and
to those trapped by the recent outbreak."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council demanded an immediate halt to the
fighting and called upon all parties to abide by the provisions of
the ceasefire agreement on the Democratic Republic of Congo, which
they signed in Lusaka on July 10," the statement said. "They urged
the parties to implement the reported ceasefire announced today."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council called upon the leaders of the
Congolese Rally for Democracy to resolve their differences and to
sign the ceasefire agreement on the Democratic Republic of Congo
without further delay and abide by its provisions," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"They called upon all concerned to ensure respect for human
rights and international humanitarian law," th statement said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday said that weekend
fighting in the Democratic Republic of Congo violated a truce to
enable millions of children to be vaccinated against polio.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here through his spokesman, Annan said,
"It is unacceptable that this fighting is taking place during the
national immunization days, which were supposed to provide the
opportunity for some 10 million children to be immunized against
polio."
</P>
<P>
"This development violates a truce for the period of August 2
to 20 endorsed by all parties following a request made by the
secretary-general," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Six African countries involved in a year-long rebellion in
Congo (K) signed a ceasefire accord in Lusaka, the Zambian
capital, on July 10. But rivalry between two factions of the rebel
Congolese Rally for Democracy opposed to President Laurent Kabila
prevented them from signing the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
