<HEADLINE> Israel Denies Involvement in Killing of Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli army chief of staff
Shaul Mofaz Tuesday denied charges that Israel was behind the
bombing death of a senior Hezbollah official in south Lebanon,
saying the killing was possibly an internal struggle in
Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli army does not get involved in internal disputes
between terrorist organizations in Lebanon," Mofaz told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Two roadside bombs exploded outside the port city of Sidon in
Lebanon Monday afternoon, killing Ali Hassan Deeb, the
coordinator for Hezbollah operations in south Lebanon. He had
been on the top of Israel's most wanted list for carrying out
attacks against the Israeli army in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah blamed Israel for the bombing attack and vowed
retaliation, but Mofaz said he suspected that Deeb had been blown
up by a rival group in Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said on Israeli television that
Israel is not the only enemy of Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a war of attrition to
oust Israeli troops and their local militia South Lebanon Army
from the so-called security zone Israel carved out in south
Lebanon in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting northern Israel
from cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army gave no orders to residents of the north to
take to bomb shelters overnight following Deeb's
killing. Hezbollah guerrillas often fired rockets and mortars into
northern Israel in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Israeli radio and television reports said there was
intensified fighting between the Israeli army and Hezbollah
guerrillas in southern Lebanon Tuesday, but they did not confirm
nor deny reports from Lebanon that one Israeli soldier was killed
and three others were injured in the clash in the occupation
zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
