<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Researchers Find High Yield Rice Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An Ethiopian agricultural
research center announced Tuesday that it has found a new,
high-yield rice species after a three-year long cross-breeding
research.
</P>
<P>
Teshale Assefa, general manager of the Pawe Research Center,
said that the new rice species, labeled as "Pawe 1", was also
disease and drought resistant.
</P>
<P>
"Pawe 1" could yield as high as 35 quintals per hectare, he
said, adding that farmers in the country normally harvest 10
quintals of rice per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The newly developed rice seed, which has got the recognition of
the National Seed Patent Approving Committee, has been distributed
to farmers.
</P>
<P>
The Pawe Research Center, located 570 kms northwest of Addis
Ababa, was founded in 1980.  
</P>
</TEXT>
