<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Rejects US Accusation of Selling Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Romanian steel tubes producers
rejected the accusation of having sold steel tubes at dumping
prices in the United States, saying the accusation is groundless.
</P>
<P>
"Romania's output is not so high as to affect the American
market," general manager of Metanef SA Stefan Marginean was quoted
Tuesday by the official Rompres news agency as saying. Metanef SA
is one of the main producers of steel tubes of Romania.
</P>
<P>
The production in metallurgy, including the stock was worth
71,092 billion lei (about 4,443 billion U.S. dollars) over
January-June, of which 4,916 billion lei (307 million U.S.
dollars) worth of tubes went to export, Stefan Marginean said,
adding that the output dropped from the similar period of last
year. It stood at 62 percent of that of the first six month of
1998.
</P>
<P>
The exports of crude iron, iron and steel were worth 258
million U.S. dollars, or 59 percent of the exports of the first
six months of 1998, when the exports of products of crude iron,
iron and steel dropped 32 percent compared to the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Commission for International Trade of the United
States accused Romania, together with Japan, Mexico, Czech
Republic and South Africa, of having sold steel at dumping prices
on the American market. The case is now being studied by the U.S.
Department of Commerce and a decision regarding the dumping price
is to be made around December 7.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
