<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda Agree to Cease Fire Between them in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda agreed Tuesday
evening on a cease-fire between the two armed forces in Kisangani
in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after marathon talks between Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan Vice President and Minister
of Defense Paul Kagame in western Uganda, Uganda's presidential
office said.
</P>
<P>
The two governments agreed on the modalities for the
implementation of the cease-fire and on no more verbal battles in
the media by officials of either country.
</P>
<P>
They also reaffirmed their commitment to cooperate with the
verification teams from Zambia and South Africa and agreed upon a
common position on the question of securing signatures to the
Lusaka cease-fire accord.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also reaffirmed their commitment to the
peaceful resolution of the conflict in the Congo and to quick
implementation of the Lusaka's cease-fire accord signed on July 10
by six relevant states.
</P>
<P>
Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) and Rwanda Patriotic Army
(RPA) have been involved in clashes in Kisangani, a conspicuous
indication of the two neighbors' difference over the strategies to
be used in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two traditional allies agreed to halt
hostilities in the central African country. However, the
atmosphere in Kisangani remains tense with all the troops of the
two sides put on full alert.
</P>
<P>
After the main rebel group -- the Congolese Rally for Democracy
-- split into two headed by Emile IIlunga and Wamba dia Wamba
respectively in mid-May, Uganda and Rwanda began to back rival
factions.
</P>
<P>
They have been trading accusations and harsh words about each
other ever since. The latest exchange of gunfire prompted the two
leaders to meet in a bid to narrow their differences.  
</P>
</TEXT>
