<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Renews Condemnation of U.S. Attack on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Sudan on Tuesday renewed it
condemnation of the U.S. air strike against Al-Shefaa
Pharmaceutical Factory in Khartoum under the pretext of it
production of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on the occasion of the first anniversary
of the air strike, the Sudanese Foreign Ministry urged the
U.N. Security Council to shoulder its full responsibility and sent
a fact-finding mission to Sudan to define the nature of the
destroyed factory.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration should accept the results of the
fact-finding committee and compensate for the human and material
damage inflicted on Sudan by the missile attack, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"The world became fully aware of the fallacy of the
U.S. allegations and the unseemly reasoning on which the United
States based its attack against the plant," it added, noting that
the United States is still fabricating charges against Sudan and
inciting Sudan's neighbors to maintain the embargo on the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on the international community to help
Sudan defense its sovereignty and territorial integrity and
to support its efforts aimed at halting the U.S. hostile acts.
</P>
<P>
It also urged "the international family" to bring pressure on
the United States until the latter respects the international
legitimacy and stop its threats to the sovereignty of other states.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sudanese Foreign Ministry called on the United
States to shoulder its responsibility as a superpower for
preserving international security and peace.
</P>
<P>
The United States has maintained a flagrant intransigence and
neglected institutional and constitutional developments in
Sudan over the last ten years, the statement pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Among such developments are the national reconciliation
initiatives, dialogues, the multi-party politics, the improvement
of relations with neighboring countries as well as with the
European Union, the cooperation with the Organization of African
Unity in the human relief area, and the protection of human
rights, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The statement underlined that the developments were praised by
the U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The United States launched a missile attack on the Shefaa plant
on August 20, 1998, alleging that it was a terrorist base and
accusing Sudan of involvement in the bombing of the two
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Sudan denied the charges categorically and called from the very
beginning on the U.N. Security Council to send a fact-finding
mission to prove its innocence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
