<HEADLINE> Pornography on Internet Causing Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 17(Xinhua) -- Child pornography on the internet
continues to be a matter of concern both regionally and
internationally, a Norwegian official from the Center for
Prevention of Child Sexual Abuse said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing participants to a conference on the prevention of
abuse on women and children which ends Wednesday, Lars Gronseth,
Deputy Director of information for the Save Children's Project in
Norway said experience had shown that a huge amount of documented
abuse of children was being distributed through the internet on
web sites.
</P>
<P>
He said the lack of legislation in different countries made it
difficult to stop and that lack of experience in the police with
these kinds of crimes made it difficult to combat.
</P>
<P>
"Until production, distribution and possession of child
pornography is illegal in every country in the world, this is a
lost battle. My hope is that people in Africa also will join this
fight and help to save the children," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gronseth said the most important resource on this battle at the
moment are the net users themselves.
</P>
<P>
As the number of internet users grows, so do the risks of
children being exposed to inappropriate materials, in particular
criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
At present not enough was known about the scale or extent of
pornographic activities on the net, their consequences and impact
on young people.
</P>
<P>
Global estimates showed that 200 million users would be
connected to the net by the year 2001 from 20 million in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
