<HEADLINE> Austrian Defense Minister on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Defense Minister
Werner Fasslabend Tuesday expressed the wish that there would
come new political movement, a unifying process for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Cyprus' Larnaca airport, Fasslabend said ways
should be found for people in Cyprus to live together in the
future, noting however that such task is not easy to achieve.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Fasslabend is in Cyprus to mark the 25th anniversary of the
death of three Austrian soldiers, killed in Larnaca district,
while on patrol during the 1974 Turkish invasion.
</P>
<P>
The three soldiers were serving in the Austrian contingent of
the U.N. Peace-keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
"This is an occasion to think over the whole situation,
especially to think of the people who had to give their lives in
order to try to bring a little bit of peace and stability here to
the situation," Fasslabend said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he will not meet any Cypriot government
officials because he will be in Cyprus for a short time. He is
expected to leave Wednesday for Lebanon to inspect the Austrian
peace-keepers there.
</P>
<P>
He said his message to Cypriots is that they will "have to
live together" in the future.
</P>
<P>
Fasslabend, who is accompanied by a 12-member delegation, said
he will not visit the northern Cyprus during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet U.N. Special Representative for Cyprus
Dame Ann Hercus, and UNFICYP commander Major-General Evergisto
Arturo de Vergara.
</P>
<P>
Fasslabend will also inspect the 250-strong Austrian
contingent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
