<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Help Uganda Combat Nile Weeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian minister said on
Tuesday that Egypt is to help Uganda combat weeds in the Nile by
providing it with a fund to buy equipment in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Works and Water Resources Mahmoud Abu Zeid
told visiting Ugandan officials that Egypt will grant 13.9 million
U.S. dollars for their country to buy the equipment for combating
the water-sucking hyacinth weed in the Nile, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Abu Zeid reviewed the specifications of the equipment needed in
the weed-combating with the officials from Uganda's ministries of
agriculture and water resources.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Ugandan officials, who arrived in Cairo
earlier in the day, briefed Abu Zeid on the problem of hyacinth,
which blocks the Nile River in the Great Lakes region, especially
during the rain season.
</P>
<P>
Water weeds are known to accelerate water evaporation in
addition to being an irritating hurdle to fishing, especially in
the Great Lakes region where fish is a staple diet.
</P>
<P>
Hyacinth also blocks river navigation routes linking Uganda
with Tanzania and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ministry of Public Works and Water Resources signed
with the Ugandan Ministry of Agriculture last March an agreement
on cooperation in combating weeds in the Nile in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
