<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatized Firms Creating More Jobs in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- More and more jobs are creating
by privatized companies in the country, the Zambia Privatization
(ZPA) Agency has said.
</P>
<P>
Acting ZPA chief executive Stuart Cruickshank told reporters in
a press conference here Tuesday that the privatization program has
been successful since a lot of jobs were saved which would not
have been the case if the companies were allowed to collapse, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that job losses has been fairly small compared to
the liberalization programs in other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said though 3,000 jobs in the trading sector had been lost,
the sector created 4,500 jobs after the privatization and there
has been the knock-on effect which has also created more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Many companies have set up other smaller companies which has
created numerous jobs in all sectors in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cruickshank further said ZPA was in the process of working with
private donors to check on the post privatization effect.
</P>
<P>
He said there is need to monitor all companies that were sold
so that an overall picture can be gotten through the collection of
data.
</P>
<P>
According to the ZPA, the majority of participants in the
Zambia privatization program are locals who have purchased small-
and medium-size state-owned assets covering the entire spectrum of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Out of 250 companies and units privatized by the ZPA, 65
percent have been bought by Zambian citizens while the remaining
35 percent have been bought by foreign investors who bought mostly
larger companies.
</P>
<P>
The majority of employees in privatized companies will always
be locals because they work happily in their country, the ZPA
said. 
</P>
