<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Bears No Enmity Against US: Khatami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Tuesday again signaled his hallmark detente with the
U.S., saying Iran has "no enmity against American nation."
</P>
<P>
"Rather we respect them and welcome cultural, social and
sports relations between the two nations," Khatami said in a
meeting with visiting Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura,
who is here on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office two years ago, the moderate Iranian
president has been advocating a dialog between the two nations,
while ruling out the possibility of talks between the two
governments in the offing.
</P>
<P>
"Americans have done many injustices toward us and it is
natural that as long as the injustices are not compensated in
practice, the wall of mistrust will not be removed," Khatami was
quoted by the official Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He criticized American policy makers for changing their
words only, but not deeds toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the U.S. severed their relations in 1980 and the
U.S. has kept its sanctions against Iran intact.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. accuses Iran of producing mass destruction weapons
and violating human rights and at the same time wants it to sit
down at negotiating table," Khatami complained.
</P>
<P>
"Our defense budget is less than that of all the regional
states; as far as atomic energy is concerned, Iran's activity is
under full supervision of the International Atomic Energy Agency,
while Israel, which has nuclear weapons, is not ready to be
submissive to them," he protested.
</P>
<P>
He accused West countries of trying to unilaterally impose
their policies on other nations despite they are "double-standard
and discriminatory."
</P>
<P>
However, Iran is firmly determined to follow the policy of
detente.
</P>
<P>
"Decreasing enmities and increasing friendship will be
continued unabated at any cost due to ideological beliefs and
principled policies," he added.
</P>
<P>
Khatami told the Japanese minister that Iran welcomes
expansion of relations with Tokyo in all fields.
</P>
<P>
" Iran hopes to get more much-needed investments from Japan, a
close ally of the U.S.," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran and Japan, both Asian countries, are inter-linked
in their destiny, and hoped Komura's visit, the first in years,
would mark a new phase in good bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The president also said Iran is to turn itself into a
democratic and civil society. There have been a number of
problems, he said, but "patience, persistence and prudence are the
road to victory."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Komura welcomed Khatami's proposal of dialog
among civilizations and praised his efforts in sponsoring reforms
and improving Iran's relations with regional and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese minister arrived here on Monday. On Tuesday, he
met with his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi, former President
Hashemi Rafsanjani and Majlis (parliament) speaker Ali Akbar
Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Komura
invited Khatami to visit Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
