<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Negotiators Meet on Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators met Tuesday in a continued effort to work out a
timetable for the implementation of the U.S.-brokered Wye
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat resumed their talks in
Jerusalem Tuesday afternoon after they failed to resolve their
difference on the timetable in their negotiations at the Erez
border crossing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office on July 6, Barak has promised to carry out
the Wye agreement, signed and then frozen by his hard-line
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu last year, but proposed some
changes to the accord, under which Israel has to hand over 13
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have reluctantly accepted his proposal to
begin implementation of the agreement at the beginning of
September and carry out the second stage of troop withdrawal on
October 1.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides have been at odds over Barak's proposal to
postpone the final stage of the deal until February 2000, when
the final-status talks dealing with thorny issues like Jerusalem
and settlements are supposed to have been well under way.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have rejected the delay and called on Barak
to complete the implementation of the final stage by mid-November
in line with the original timetable of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
During their talks Sunday, Sher and Erekat failed to make a
breakthrough on the withdrawal issue but made progress on some
secondary issues, including the release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
A joint Israeli-Palestinian committee met Tuesday for the
first time to discuss the issue of prisoners amid signs that
Israel might agree to release the so-called "security prisoners,"
referring to those Palestinians who were jailed for participating
in attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami from the Labor Party
said Tuesday that there is logic in Palestinians' demand that all
security prisoners be released under the framework of a permanent
peace agreement, saying internal discussions were taking place
concerning the release of those prisoners under the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
Israel released 250 Palestinian prisoners last November, the
first group of 750 prisoners to be released in three stages under
the Wye agreement. But most of the released were common criminals
instead of security prisoners the Palestinian National Authority
had required.
</P>
<P>
The dispute sparked weeks of bloodiest violence in years
between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in the West Bank and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Israel's security cabinet will hold a special meeting
Wednesday to discuss the issue of Palestinian prisoner release,
Israeli media said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Get Tougher with Attackers on Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Majlis (parliament) is
about to approve tougher punishments for attackers on foreign
tourists, apparently in reaction to the kidnapping of four
foreigners in the southern province of Kerman Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
It was announced here Tuesday that a number of Majlis deputies
are to present a draft bill to beef up the effort of cracking
down on abducting and attacking foreign tourists, an act seen as
tarnishing the country's image as a safe place for investment
and tourism.
</P>
<P>
The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Mohsen Emani,
deputy head of Iran Tourism Organization, as saying that if the
bill is approved, tough punishments will wait for those offenders.
</P>
<P>
Three Spanish tourists, an Italian and an Iranian guide were
abducted from a Kerman hotel by three men and two women armed
with automatic weapons, believed to be linked with drug
trafficking. Local security forces were negotiating with the
kidnappers for their safe release.
</P>
<P>
A similar incident happened in June in the same province when
three Italians were kidnapped. They were released a week later
after the Interior Ministry intervened to negotiate with the
abductors.
</P>
<P>
There has been criticism of the dealing with kidnappers. Had
tougher measures be imposed, local newspapers said, the latest
kidnapping would not have happened.
</P>
<P>
The papers called the kidnapping as targeting Iran's security,
foreign and domestic investment as well as Iran's international
image, and urged security apparatus to find the root cause of the
problem and solve it as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry on Sunday condemned the kidnapping,
calling it an "inhuman and ugly" act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
