<HEADLINE> Lebanon Condemns Killing of Hezbollah Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
and Prime Minister Salim Hoss Tuesday strongly condemned the
killing of a senior military officer of the anti-Israeli
guerrilla group Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
"The crime which was perpetrated by the enemy (Israel) will
not affect Lebanese people's determination to defend and restore
their land," Lahoud said when meeting with visiting Saudi
Princess Muna Riyad Salah.
</P>
<P>
Hoss told reporters that it is a tragic for Lebanon to see a
great struggler fall to join the long caravan of martyrs of the
resistance.
</P>
<P>
He called the assassination a "treacherous Israeli action,"
saying Israel had habituated them to such kind of crimes which
targeted not only the country's resistance but all Lebanese
people.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah military officer Ali Deeb, known as Abu Hassan
Salameh, was killed Monday near the country's southern coastal
city of Sidon when a bomb tore apart his car.
</P>
<P>
There has been no group claiming responsibility for the
attack. Hezbollah swiftly blamed the killing on Israel and vowed
to exact revenge.
</P>
<P>
But, Israel denied any involvement in the killing and
attributed it to Hezbollah's rival groups.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli army does not get involved in internal disputes
between terrorist organizations in Lebanon," Israeli army chief of
staff Shaul Mofaz told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is spearheading
a guerrilla group trying to oust Israeli occupation forces out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
