<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges Afghan Parties to End Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday called on Afghan warring factions to
immediately end the conflict and take measures to ensure the
protection of civilians.
</P>
<P>
He also urged them to ensure the safe and free movement of
international humanitarian assistants, his deputy spokesman Manoel
de Almeida e Silva told a press briefing at the U.N. headquarters
in New York.
</P>
<P>
Annan noted that "the primary responsibility for the welfare of
the Afghan civilians rests with those who have displaced them from
their homes."
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by reports of violations affecting inhabitants of the
Shomali plain north of Kabul, the capital, the Secretary-General
strongly condemned the ongoing forceful displacement of civilians
as a result of the most recent offensive by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban movement, currently in control of 90 percent of
Afghanistan, this month launched the new offensive against the
North Alliance, but it has met strong counter-attacks.
</P>
<P>
The offensive has produced more displacements with 10,000
reported over the weekend and a further 9,000 moving into Kabul on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Continuing fighting has made Afghanistan one of the biggest
refugee sources with 2.2 million Afghans in Iran and another 1.6
million in Pakistan, according to U.N. figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
