<HEADLINE> 8 Iraqi Civilians Killed in U.S.-British Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Eight Iraqi civilians were
killed and 10 others injured on Tuesday in U.S.-British
warplanes' attacks on residential areas and military sites in
northern and southern Iraq, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:35 (0635 GMT) 11 formations of
U.S. and British warplanes coming from Turkish airspace violated
northern Iraqi airspace over Neineva, Erbil and Dohuk provinces.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes attacked some civilian and service facilities,
residential areas as well as military sites in the region,
killing eight civilians and injuring nine others, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 14:07 (1007 GMT) 12 formations of
U.S.-British warplanes coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases
violated southern Iraqi airspace over Basrah, Thi-Qar, Qadisiyah,
Misan and Wasit provinces.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes bombed some civilian and service installations
and military sites in this region, injuring one civilian, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the enemy planes and
forced them to flee to their bases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have made over 11,500 sorties over the two
no-fly zones in Iraq, and have been regularly attacking Iraqi
civilian facilities and military sites.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led western
allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
