<HEADLINE> ECOWAS to Hold Mini-Summit on Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) is scheduled to hold a mini-summit in an
effort to end the new clashes between rebels and Liberian
government forces along the border with Guinea.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate was quoted as saying
Tuesday in Nigerian capital Abuja that the proposed summit,
involving the Mano River Union member states -- Liberia, Sierra
Leone and Guinea -- would also be attended by Ghana, Nigeria and
Togo.
</P>
<P>
"It is a serious problem involving two of our member countries
with security implications for the entire community and we cannot
allow dissidents to undermine the peace which we all fought for
in Liberia,'' Kouyate said.
</P>
<P>
Armed groups fighting against the government of President
Charles Taylor invaded Liberia last week, seizing some territories
on the country's border with Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate said that the conflicts are diverting the efforts of
the 16- nation group away from economic development and regional
integration, adding that "we should be engaged in harmonization
of policies to accelerate integration instead of dissipating
energies on mutual suspicion and conflicts.'' 
</P>
