<HEADLINE> Bangladesh High Court Issues Contempt Rule Upon Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's High Court on Tuesday
issued rules upon the editors, printers and publishers of four
national dailies directing them to show cause why contempt
proceedings should not be drawn against them, the BSS news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The High Court directed the editors, printers and publishers
and some reporters of "Daily Sangbad (Daily News)," "Daily
Janakantha (Daily People's Voice)," "Prothom Alo (First Light),"
and "The Bangladesh Observer" to appear before the court on August
24 to explain why contempt proceedings should not be drawn against
them "for willfully publishing false and fabricated reports with
the motive to lower the image of the Supreme Court of the
country."
</P>
<P>
The rule was issued following a petition filed by senior
advocate Habibul Islam Bhuiyan.
</P>
<P>
In his petition, Bhuiyan said that Daily Sangbad on October 12,
1998, Daily Janakantha on October 12, 1998, Daily Prothom Alo on
November 4, 1998 and The Bangladesh Observer on October 6, 1998
had published false statements which lowered the image of the
highest court of the country and created confusion among the
judges and the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
A report in the Daily Star newspaper said that on August 10,
the High Court in a suo moto rule directed the editor, publisher
and printer of the Banglabazar Patrika and a dismissed employee of
the Supreme Court to be present in the court on August 25 to show
cause as to why they should not be punished for committing
contempt of court by publishing contemptuous news.
</P>
<P>
The court in the order observed that news items published in
the newspaper on August 5, 1999 under headlines "(President)
Shahabuddin (Ahmed) took oath by breaching oath," and "for
establishing rule of law Shahabuddin be impeached" contain
materials in which the Supreme Court and its judges have been
deliberately maligned and scandalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
