<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Reports Higher Re-Export Share in 1st Half of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) witnessed a higher re-export shares
of its total value of external trade in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The figures released by the Census and Statistics Department (
CSD) Tuesday show that the Hong Kong's re-exports in the first
half of 1999 accounted for 87.2 percent of the value of its total
exports and 42.7 percent of the total value of external trade.
</P>
<P>
The re-exports are slightly higher than the corresponding
shares of 86.2 percent and 41.0 percent in the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the report by the CSD, the Chinese mainland
remained the largest partner for Hong Kong's re-export trade, with
re-exports from the Chinese mainland accounting for 59.9 percent
of the value of re-exports of Hong Kong in the first half of 1999.
As a destination, the Chinese mainland's share was 34.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the re-export trade involving the Chinese mainland is
related to outward processing, as raw materials and semi-
manufactures are exported to the mainland for processing, with the
final products subsequently returned to Hong Kong and then re-
exported to overseas markets, it said.
</P>
<P>
Other main origins of Hong Kong's re-exports include Japan (
accounting for 10.4 percent), Taiwan (6.3 percent), the United
States (5.1 percent) and the Republic of Korea (3.4 percent),
while other main destinations including the United States (
accounting for 22.3 percent), Japan (5.7 percent), Germany (3.6
percent) and the United Kingdom (3.6 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
