<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Construction Rises Again in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. construction of new
homes and apartments rose 5.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.66 million units in July, the Commerce Department
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
July's advance was better than analysts had been expecting,
reflecting continued strength in the U.S. housing sector despite
rising mortgage rates. Housing starts had fallen 5.8 percent in
June.
</P>
<P>
The report said new home construction was up in all parts of
the country except for the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
Mortgage rates have been rising since the beginning of the year
and last week the average rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage
soared to 8.15 percent, the highest in more than than two years.
this year.
</P>
<P>
The West led the way in new home construction last month with a
22.7 percent gain. In the South, new home construction was up 8.5
percent and in the Northeast 6.3 percent. But in the Midwest new
home construction was down 16.8 percent last month.  
</P>
