<HEADLINE> Material Support for Landmine Victims Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) Tuesday stressed the need to work out practical modalities
to ensure necessary material and social support for landmine
victims.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here on assistance to landmine victims in Burundi,
 Mozambique and Uganda, WHO Regional Director for Africa Ebrahim
Samba said this support would enable them to live a meaningful
life.
</P>
<P>
He told delegates that immediate assistance should include the
provision of orthopaedic walking devices to victims and the
training of technicians to produce such devices.
</P>
<P>
Other assistance, he said, also involves the training of
technicians to deal with injuries resulting from mine explosions,
clearing mines and the physical and mental rehabilitation of
victims.
</P>
<P>
Africa is one of the most mine-affected areas of the world and
experts estimate that worldwide, one person is killed or injured
every 15 minutes by landmines.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was being attended by delegates from the three
African countries, the WHO and the International Committee of the
Red Cross. 
</P>
