<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: VAT Goes into Full Enforcement in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Value Added Tax (VAT) finally
went into complete enforcement in Nepal on Tuesday, after nearly
two years' confusion over it since the government attempted to
implement it last November.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mahesh Acharya took a bold step in his annual
budget for the fiscal year 1998/99 to end the unusually protracted
confusion over the tax policy. He unilaterally revoked the
39-point agreement on VAT reached by the previous government with
the business community that compromised with the basics of VAT.
</P>
<P>
With a hope to bring more tax payers under VAT net, Acharya
scaled down the VAT threshold to 2 million rupees (about 29,400
U.S. dollars) from earlier 4.5 million (66,200 U.S. dollars),
requiring virtually every potential businessman to register with
VAT.
</P>
<P>
The threshold level was at the center of the VAT dispute in the
past two years, while a section of business community led by Nepal
Chamber of Commerce opposed VAT. They fear VAT will slice off
significant portion of their profit and will make them
uncompetitive with foreign rivals.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, has no option but VAT. Nepal's total
tax revenue as a share of GDP is one of the lowest in the world.
It hovers around 11 percent as against over 30 percent in the
developed countries and over 20 percent average among the
countries in the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is currently reeling under the pressure of swindling tax
and tariff rates. In the last seven years since Nepal took liberal
economic policy in 1992, all the additional income tax rates have
been waived and highest customs tariffs have been slashed to 40
percent from over 100 percent (except for luxurious goods). The
highest income tax rates have been reduced to 25 percent from 50
percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The pressing imperatives of international trade and regional
trade have made upward revision of tax and tariffs unfeasible.
Under this circumstance, the government hopes to improve revenue
mobilization by expanding tax base under VAT.
</P>
<P>
The business community showed no sign of opposition to the
threshold revision so far. They seem to have found common ground
with the government regarding VAT. But consumers may be
immediately affected by the tax rule.
</P>
<P>
According to some businessmen, VAT will not affect price
theoretically. But practically, prices of commodities will rise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: China's Progress Most Remarkable: Former Nepal FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 17 (Xinhua) -- China has made the most
remarkable achievements in the world over the past 50 years under
the leadership of the Communist Party of China, former Nepali
prime minister Sher Bahadur Deuba said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Progress that China has made in the last five decades is
one of the most remarkable achievements done by any country in
this century," said Deuba, who was Nepali prime minister from
September 1995 to March 1997.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua at his residence, Deuba paid
tribute to the great contributions the Communist Party of China
and the Chinese people have made to China's economic development
and the lift-up of China's international status.
</P>
<P>
"The far-sightedness of the leaders of the Communist Party of
China and the discipline, sacrifice and hard-working of its people
has resulted in tangible development in all sectors and the global
acknowledgment of China as one of the world's biggest markets.
Debilitating poverty seems to have been left behind by most of
China," said Deuba.
</P>
<P>
Deuba visited China in April 1996 at the invitation of the then
Chinese Premier Li Peng, and met with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin as well as other senior Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
Deuba said he was very much impressed by China's economic
progress as well as China's ancient and great civilization during
the visit.
</P>
<P>
"China's progress towards a socialist market economy and its
establishment as an important world leader is very admirable," he
told Xinhua, adding that the impression of a modern China will
always remain with him.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day visit to China, Deuba visited Beijing, the
ancient city of Xi'an and Shengzhen, a boom city in South China.
He saw for himself both the modern and ancient civilization of
China.
</P>
<P>
Deuba said that landmarks of China's ancient civilization such
as the Great Wall and the terra-cotta warriors in Xi'an are the
miracles of the world.
</P>
<P>
He marvelled at the successful integration of the modern
development and the ancient heritage by the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"The ability of the Chinese people to take in the new without
forgetting the old was what I found most remarkable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Tried, tested and revered values, norms and beliefs have been
assimilated and woven into the fabric of modern China," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Sagacity has been adopted in the process of development and
the resulting stability and sustainable economic growth of China
struck me as being most impressive," Deuba said.
</P>
<P>
As former prime minister and now a member of parliament, Deuba
expressed his appreciation for China's assistance to Nepal in its
economic development and China's support for Nepal, a close and
good neighbor of China's, in preserving its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"Nepal regards China as its most trusted friend," as "China has
helped Nepal not only in its development programs but also
contributed to preserving Nepal's identity and sovereignty," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure the age-old friendly relations between our two
countries will be further strengthened in the coming centuries,"
Deuba said.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic of China (on October 1, 1999) and as the new
century approaching, Deuba conveyed his best wishes to China and
the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"I wish all the leaders and citizens of China the best for the
coming millennium and hope their pride in being citizens of a
peaceful and prosperous China becomes even stronger globally,"
said Deuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
