<HEADLINE> Canada Bans Blood Donation by Britain Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada is imposing a ban on blood
donation by those visiting Britain for six months or more between
1980 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Health Canada said Tuesday that the ban, which takes effect on
February 17, 2000, is intended to reduce possibility of
transmitting "mad cow" disease by means of blood transfusion.
</P>
<P>
Health Canada decided on the ban following months of
consultations with the Canadian Blood Serives and Hema-Quebec,
which is also an operator of the national blood service, the
federal department said.
</P>
<P>
There have been concerns about the spreading of
Creutzfeld-Jakob or "mad cow" disease, which is believed
communicable by eating infected beef or through contaminated
blood.
</P>
<P>
No cure has yet been found for the neurological disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
