<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Mine Clearing Hampered by Funds Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Land mine clearance is being
hampered by limited financial support from governments and donor
agencies, a local company which specializes in the removal of land
mines said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Marketing Director of the Mine-Tech Company Chris Pearce said
funds for de-mining activities throughout the world were limited
and donor support had been flagging in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing guests attending a demonstration of mine
survey and clearance technique in Harare, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the 1997 historic mine-ban treaty signed by 127
countries in Canada could have led to the decline in donor support
for de-mining activities throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
He said the treaty, known as the Ottawa Convention, had made
some donors and companies believe that the treaty had solved the
land mine problem.
</P>
<P>
Pearce said the land mine problem was there to stay, and the
only solution was to get rid of the land-mines which were already
planted.
</P>
<P>
There were 110 million mines planted throughout the world, of
which a little over one third were in Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations, nearly two million mines were
planted every year while only 200,000 were removed.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that, with the current pace of mine clearance
operations, it would take more than 1,100 years to rid the planet
of already planted mines provided no new mines were laid.
</P>
<P>
Pearce said land mines denied the majority of the people in
developing countries access to land and agriculture, which formed
the basis of their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
He cited an example of Angola which he said was rich in oil and
diamond, but the riches were not benefiting the Angolans as they
could not access them because of mines.
</P>
<P>
Mine-Tech was formed in 1992 and has worked for various clients
 including U.N. agencies, European Union and various
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The company has worked in many countries including Angola,
Mozambique, Nicaragua, Somalia, Zimbabwe and Srilanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Leaders Reportedly Steal $1 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- As much as one billion U.S.
dollars has disappeared in public funds and international aid
projects through fraud by the Muslim, Croatian and Serbian
nationalist leaders, The New York Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The antifraud unit, set up by the Office of the High
Representative, has exposed so much corruption that relief
agencies and embassies are reluctant to publicize the thefts for
fear of frightening away international donors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper obtained a report by the unit that names several
officials with ties to the governing nationalist parties, accusing
them of profiting from the fraud.
</P>
<P>
Although 15 officials have been dismissed by the High
Representative or have been blocked from holding office, most
retain authority, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"Organizations as diverse at the Office of the High
Representative, the United Nations and the United States Agency
for International Development, all dedicated to rebuilding the
country, have lost tens of millions of dollars," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report, which has not been made public, cites one incident
in which 10 foreign embassies and international aid agencies lost
more than 20 million U.S. dollars deposited in a Bosnian bank.
</P>
<P>
The unit is investigating 220 cases of alleged fraud and
corruption. The funds were meant to help rebuild Bosnia's roads,
buildings and schools and to provide municipal services in towns
across the country.
</P>
<P>
"Alija Izetbegovic, the Bosnian president along with other
senior nationalist leaders, has dismissed the allegations of
official corruption made by the international investigators," the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The corruption has also played a pivotal role in driving away
foreign investment, seen as the only way to free Bosnia from
dependence on foreign assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
