<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Death Toll Rises to 1,400 in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The overall death toll in the
strong earthquake in Turkey has climbed to 1,400 and the number of
the injured has risen to more than 6,000, the local media reported
late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands more people are still missing and are feared dead.
</P>
<P>
An oil refinery not far form the epicenter of Izmit has been
caught in a fire and might incur an explosion, a local official
said, adding residents in the surrounding areas have been
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said he believes the loss
of lives will be huge, "but, God willing, we will not be faced
with a picture as bad as we fear."
</P>
<P>
However, the indications point to a grim tally.
</P>
<P>
Layer by layer from thousands of sites around western Turkey,
the ruins gave up the dead - many in the pajamas and nightgowns
they wore when the immense temblor struck with 45 seconds of
terror and destruction in the cool hours before dawn.
</P>
<P>
As many as 10, 000 people could still be trapped in rubble
around Golcuk, a navy base town about 130 kilometers southeast of
Istanbul and near the quake's epicenter.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake was the worst ever to strike western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers dug with everything from bare hands to picks and
shovels.
</P>
<P>
The United States, France, Israel and Egypt, among other
countries, have dispatched relief material and personnel to Turkey
to help the country to pass the difficult time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
