<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Branded Most Risky Place For Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANA quoted one of the organization's statement published
Monday as saying that 10 journalists got killed in their work in
Sierra Leone during the first eight months this year against the
background of wide-spread atrocities against civilians.
</P>
<P>
The RSF said 20 journalists were killed worldwide in the same
period, a figure larger than that of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia came second with six journalists killed, Nigeria has
two, Colombia and Lebanon one, respectively, according to the
organization's statement.
</P>
<P>
''The murder of journalists is often a good indicator of the
suffering endured by the rest of the population,'' the RSF said,
adding that in January alone, eight journalists were murdered by
the Revolutionary United Front, former rebels of Sierra Leone
before the July 7 Lome peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The organization said two journalists covering clashes between
rival ethnic groups were also murdered in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
''RSF is particularly concerned because most of the crimes
committed against journalists are likely to remain unpunished, the
reluctance of many governments to track down and punish those who
killed journalists can only encourage the continuation of these
crimes,'' it said in its Monday statement.
</P>
<P>
The RSF noted that even after the recent 50th anniversary
celebrations of the Geneva Conventions, some states are incapable
of protecting civilians, particularly journalists, in war time.
</P>
<P>
The organization urged all states signatory to the Geneva
Conventions to respect their commitments by protecting
journalists' basic right to life as well as giving courts and
committees of inquiry the necessary resources to find and punish
those who murder journalists
</P>
<P>
The organization observed that in Europe the conflict between
Serbia and NATO countries hit the media hard with three Chinese
journalists killed when their embassy was bombed in Belgrade by
NATO aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
