<HEADLINE> Immigration Target Unchanged, Canadian Minister Reaffirms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Immigration Minister
Elinor Caplan Tuesday reaffirmed the country won't change its
current target of a yearly 225,000 immigrants, according to a CTV
report.
</P>
<P>
She was denying reports that the federal government is
considering a move to more than double that target to 500,000.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the on-going three-day Liberal caucus retreat in
Halifax, Nova Scotia, the minister told reporters, "At the present
time, the policy is that the targets for immigration for Canada
are between 200,000 and 225,000 people."
</P>
<P>
"There is no discussion at this time about changing that as far
as I'm aware," the minister said. "What we're attempting to do is
to see what we can do to achieve those targets."
</P>
<P>
Local reports said earlier that the country failed to meet its
immigration target in the past two years and some members of the
caucus wanted that target increased to 500,000.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Liberal Party caucus meeting, which opened Monday,
is on hot debate on ways to spend the anticipated 10 billion
Canadian dollars (67.34 billion U.S. dollars) in budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
The battle lines are drawn between tax-cut Liberal MPs and
those advocating a fall agenda aimed at new social programs for
kids, local media reports said. 
</P>
