<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes India's Nuclear Doctrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
opposed India's move to create a credible nuclear deterrence and
said it will continue efforts to encourage India abandon their
nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin described the move "in
the wrong direction" as it would create an "action-reaction cycle
that will increase the risks" to both India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
India's National Security Advisory Board on Monday released a
draft doctrine which stated that India will pursue a policy of
credible nuclear deterrence. The draft also said India will use
nuclear weapons only to retaliate against a first strike.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States would "encourage India to take
additional steps to demonstrate its declared intention to avoid a
nuclear missile race with its Neighbors."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to India's earlier indication that it could
accept the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty next month.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington had noted India's Prime Minister Atal
Vajpayee stated this week that he wanted to build a consensus on
the CTBT to allow the new government, once it is formed after
elections this fall, to approve India's joining the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
