<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Launches National Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Tuesday assured that this year's national population and housing
census would be the best, most accurate and successful in the
country's history.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks when he officially launched the
1999 population and housing census at the Kenyatta International
Conference Centre grounds in the capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"This will definitely be the most successful census we have ever
 experienced since its inception in 1948,'' Moi said.
</P>
<P>
The President urged all Kenyans to support the process, asking
communities to disregard the belief that counting people,
particularly children, was a bad omen.
</P>
<P>
The President also assured enumerators that security had been
put in place nationally and asked them to proceed with confidence.
</P>
<P>
Moi noted the census was important because it would help the
government in planning and in the execution of social and economic
needs of the people,
</P>
<P>
and also would help to measure and assess key changes that have
taken place since independence, following marked population
growth.
</P>
<P>
The data to be collected will include the fertility rate
decline, the impact of the HIV/AIDS pandemic and the extent of
urbanization. It would also help in forming effective housing
policies and social amenities.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the census, the fourth since independence and
the last this century, was the most important planning tool for
the country because it would form a strong basis for allocating
resources, document the progress made by authorities and help form
effective town development plans.
</P>
<P>
Kenyans, he said, were looking forward to a professional and
accurate census, and the government was committed to living up to
these expectations,
</P>
<P>
by ensuring among other things that the results were announced
on time.
</P>
<P>
This year's census will begin on the night of August 24 and
will continue up to August 31. It is expected that preliminary
results will be ready within six months of the census exercise.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 census will be Kenya's sixth census since 1948,
enumerated the following number of people: five million in 1948,
nine million in 1962, 11 million in 1969, 15 million in 1979 and
21 million in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The country's present population is estimated at 30 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
