as metals group Billiton extended its decline from record highs.
</P>
<P>
The major casualty in the session, Billiton had risen strongly
in recent session on hopes of consolidation in the aluminum
sector. It fell to earth Tuesday, sliding almost 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Billiton fell for the second day, after Deutsche Bank advised
investors to sell the stock and switch to Rio Tinto.
</P>
<P>
FTSE 100 decliners also included EMAP, down 33p at 1,028p, on
concern about the outlook for circulation figures and after
Deutsche Bank has cut its profit.
</P>
<P>
Shares in the FTSE 100 index which rose included SmithKline
Beecham, up 4.5p at 774p, after the company said it completed the
sale of its clinical laboratory unit.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Dax index closed up 2.81 points, or 0.05 percent, at
5,259.91, off highs as the Dow's early rally stalled.
</P>
<P>
Stocks in Paris closed up for the fifth consecutive session on
the day, after U.S. consumer prices data which was in line with
forecasts provided some cheer for players frustrated by a dearth
of corporate news.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip CAC 40 index notched up a closing gain of 0.47
percent at 4,479.75, although traders said any further advance
would be capped ahead of the Federal Reserve's monetary policy
meeting next week. 
