<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Break Traditional Education with Kart Racing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chasing after this dream, Li has been driving a kart for over
two hours every day for the past two years, despite the fact that
there is only one Chinese F1 driver among the world's top 50.
</P>
<P>
The first national kart racing for teenagers was held today in
the city of Liyang in east China's Jiangsu Province. More than 80
pupils from Beijing, Tianjin, and Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces
are taking part in the three-day competition.
</P>
<P>
"Kart driving is the cradle for F-1 racers," said Jin Xuefang,
section chief for basic education in the Ministry of Education, "
The purpose of popularizing kart driving among primary and middle
school students, however, is to offer a vehicle for quality-
oriented education which is being promoted nationwide."
</P>
<P>
The Ministry and the China Association for Science and
Technology (CAST) jointly launched a program in 1994 to enhance
the capabilities of Chinese students in mastering modern
techniques.
</P>
<P>
Karts were seen as an experiment for practicing modern-
technique education by introducing kart driving to students. In
the past, Chinese students were often asked to make jiao zi (
dumplings) or bind mops when taking technique-training courses.
</P>
<P>
Kart driving now has been introduced to some 30 primary and
middle schools in Beijing, and currently the kart is the only
motor vehicle that kids under the age of 18 can drive in China.
</P>
<P>
Jin said that quality-oriented education should be ideational
and vivid, with technique education an essential part of it. "
Technique education is an important way to improving students'
comprehensive capabilities," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Kart driving helps encourage students to put on their thinking
caps and do things with their own hands," Jin said, "This will
enable students to become familiar with scientific know-how, and
improve their coordination."
</P>
<P>
Lu Taichang, a CAST official, noted that China will not only be
repaid with F-1 racers of its own, but also with many multi-
talented people in the future, if more courses involving science
and technology are available, such as kart driving, which has now
been introduced to 930,000 primary and middle schools across China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0073 </DOCNO>
