<HEADLINE> Dhaka Announces Rehabilitation Scheme for Slum Dwellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina on Wednesday announced a series of measures for the
rehabilitation of the country's slum dwellers.
</P>
<P>
Each slum-dweller family intending to return to their ancestral
homestead in villages would be provided with travel expense, three
months' free food support and micro-credit facilities for income
generation through government institutions and agencies, the prime
minister told the first meeting of the recently-established "Slum
Dwellers Rehabilitation Committee."
</P>
<P>
Giving guidelines for proper rehabilitation of the slum
dwellers, she said the prime objective of her government was to
provide shelters to every homeless people of the country.
</P>
<P>
Because of river erosion or social deprivation, the slum people
were compelled to leave their homes and migrated to urban areas,
she said, adding that the root cause of the unending migration of
rural people to urban areas was poverty and joblessness.
</P>
<P>
These people had been living in un-hygienic condition and
leading a sub-human life in the slums of the city and were also
subjected to various types of exploitation, she said, adding the
slums became centers of crime and anti-social activities.
</P>
<P>
The measures included a survey in the slums to identity those
who had homesteads in their villages and were willing to go back
and those distressed poor people who had no way to go back to
their villages.
</P>
<P>
Estimates show that there are around 2 million slum dwellers in
Dhaka, which has a population of about 9 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
