<HEADLINE> Egypt Not Intended to Make Trouble for Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said Wednesday that its
refusal to allow an Israeli passenger plane to pass through its
airspace Tuesday was a misunderstanding of operating procedures
and Egypt had no intention to make trouble for Israeli flights.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy summoned Egypt's ambassador
to Israel Mohamed Bassiouny to explain why air-controllers in
Egypt did not allow a Boeing 747 passenger plane of Israel's
national carrier El Al to enter Egyptian airspace on its route to
Bangkok, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The plane had to return to Tel Aviv with 329 passengers on
board. The incident is the third of its kind in 10 day. Two
Israeli charter planes to Kenya were also denied entrance to
Egyptian airspace, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Bassiouny reiterated that Egypt has no diplomatic
or political intention to make difficulties for El Al flights in
Egyptian airspace and that the incidents were the result of a
misunderstanding of the standard operating procedures between the
aviation authorities," Israeli Foreign Ministry said in a
statement after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The Ambassador stated that the matter would be taken care
of," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted Egyptian civil aviation officials as saying
that Israel had failed on several occasions to request permission
to use Egyptian airspace.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel signed a peace treaty with Egypt in 1979, all
flights from Tel Aviv to Bangkok, Bombay, South Africa and Kenya
have passed over the Sinai Peninsula in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
