<HEADLINE> Russia Apologizes to Georgia for Accidental Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Wednesday apologized to
neighboring Georgia for mistakenly dropping anti-personnel mines
over the Georgian territory on August 9.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the Foreign Ministry, Russia said it
is ready to consider compensation for the inflicted damage. The
mines reportedly wounded four people.
</P>
<P>
"It has been found that in view of the combat actions taken
against the armed bands in Dagestan, a faulty discharge by a
Russian aircraft of a container with anti-personnel mines did
actually take place," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the plane "was on a mission to lay mines in the
mountain passes of Chechnya to prevent terrorists from
infiltrating into Dagestan."
</P>
<P>
The Russian side expressed "its sincere regret over the
incident," and promised to take necessary measures to "prevent
similar incidents in the future." 
