<HEADLINE> One Killed, Scores Injured in Violence in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- One young man was killed and
scores were injured in Bangladesh on Wednesday in violence during
the opposition-organized siege of the offices of deputy
commissioners (DC) across the country, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The siege of DC offices was part of the opposition's
anti-government campaign on several issues including the
government's recent decision to examine a proposal of extending
road transshipment facilities to India.
</P>
<P>
A lathe machine worker was killed and more than 40 people were
injured when unidentified gunmen attacked a procession led by the
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) marching towards the DC office
in Narayanganj, 16 kilometers southeast of the capital, police
said.
</P>
<P>
A large area of the old part of the capital came to a
standstill with shops shattered and roads blocked as BNP activists
clashed with police for nearly three hours when their march was
stopped near the DC office.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people, including four policemen, were injured
during the clash, and 13 activists were arrested following the
incident, police said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Dhaka district administration said the
opposition parties including BNP submitted a memorandum to the
deputy commissioner's office as part of their program.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance, comprising the major opposition -- the
BNP, the Jatiya Party, the Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya
Jote, earlier this month announced fresh anti-government programs,
including the siege of district DC offices across the country and
a siege of the Bangladesh Secretariat next month.
</P>
<P>
The programs were aimed at "forcing reversal of the government
plans to give transshipment facilities to India," Deputy Leader of
the Opposition in Parliament Badruddoza Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition accused the government of allowing "corridor to
India in the name of transshipment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
