<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Disruption of Israeli Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Abdel Fattah Kato, the head of
Egypt's Civil Aviation Authority, on Wednesday denied that it was
disrupting flights of Israeli planes in its airspace.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that a plane of El Al, Israel's national
carrier, flying to Johannesburg, South Africa, Tuesday night was
allowed to fly over Egypt although it did not obtain a permit in
advance.
</P>
<P>
"Clarifications have been sent more than once to the Israeli
authorities on the necessity of having a permit in advance for
their planes," Kato said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Israeli aviation agreement requires a permit in
advance to fly in each other's airspace, Kato said. He blamed
Israel for failing to observe the rules.
</P>
<P>
Israel has reportedly expressed concern over alleged flight
disruptions that its passenger planes have encountered over
Egyptian airspace.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Akiva Tor said on
Wednesday that an El Al plane to Bangkok, Thailand, was turned
back by Egyptian air controllers Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
In the last 10 days, two Israeli charter flights to Kenya also
encountered problems while flying over Egypt, Tor said. One was
turned back and the other was delayed.
</P>
<P>
Tor said Israeli planes flying to Africa and the Far East have
no other option but to fly over Egypt, one of the only two Arab
countries in the region with which it has a peace treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
