<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Former Rwandan Ministers Plead Not Guilty at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three appeared before Trial Chamber II of the United
Nations tribunal. Two pleaded not guilty to charges of genocide
and crimes against humanity and one had his plea of not guilty
entered on his behalf by the Trial Chamber after he failed to
plead, according to a statement released by the court.
</P>
<P>
The two who pleaded "not guilty" are Justin Mugenzi, 50, former
Minister of Trade and Industry, and Prosper Mugiraneza, 42, former
Minister of the Civil Service, and the Trial Chamber entered a
plea of not guilty on behalf of Jerome Bicamumpaka, 42, former
Minister of Foreign Affairs, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A fourth, Casimir Bizimungu, 48, former Minister of Health, who
is jointly charged with the three, could not enter his plea
because his assigned lawyer Judith Bourne from the United States,
has not arrived in north Tanzania's Arusha town, where the ICTR is
based.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution alleged that the accused jointly participated
in the planning, preparation or execution of a common plan, to
commit the atrocities against Tutsis and moderate Hutus in Rwanda
in 1994. At least 500,000 people in the country were killed in
the genocide.
</P>
<P>
"The crimes were committed by them personally, by persons they
assisted or by their subordinates, and with their knowledge or
consent," the prosecution told the Trial Chamber.
</P>
<P>
The crimes they were charged are alleged to have resulted in
massacres against Tutsis and moderate Hutus at a hospital in
Butare, southern Rwanda, where among those murdered was the former
Queen of Rwanda, Rosalie Gicanda, a historical symbol of all
Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
Also cited were massacres that took place at Butare University
Hospital and at the Secondary Nursing School in Kabgayi, Gitarama
Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Mugenzi is alleged to have made statements inciting people to
kill Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
Bicamumpaka and Mugiraneza are alleged to have taken no
measures to stop massacres of the civilian population. On the
contrary, they are alleged to have encouraged the killings, the
prosecution said.
</P>
<P>
Mugenzi, Bicamumpaka and Mugiraneza were arrested in Cameroon
on April 6 this year and transferred to Arusha on July 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Cooperation Between China and UPU (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The following is a brief account
of relations of cooperation between China and the Universal Postal
Union (UPU), a special institute under the United Nations:
</P>
<P>
China was in a semi-colonial, semi-feudal state when UPU was
founded in 1874. China then had no access to UPU because its
postal services were controlled by major western powers.
</P>
<P>
In 1897, China attended the UPU congress for the first time as
an observer. It sent a delegation headed by imperial envoy Wu
Tingfang to the Fifth Congress of UPU in Washington.
</P>
<P>
China officially join UPU on March 1, 1914, four decades after
the international organization was founded.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of new China in 1949, China sent
representatives to attend a meeting of the former Executive and
Liaison Council (the predecessor of the present Council of
Administration) in May, 1950, and a joint meeting of UPU and the
International Air Transport Association in January, 1951.
</P>
<P>
China also notified UPU in December, 1950 that it accepted the
Universal Postal Convention and other conventions that UPU passed
at its congress in Paris in 1947.
</P>
<P>
However, China was deprived of its legal membership in UPU in
April, 1951. As a result, China suspended its relations with UPU
for the next 21 years.
</P>
<P>
After China's legal representation was restored in the UN and
all its agencies by an overwhelming majority of votes at the 26th
UN General Assebly, UPU passed a resolution to recognize People's
Republic of China as the sole legal representative of China in UPU
on April 13, 1972.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Cooperation Between China and UPU (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As China deepened its understanding of UPU, it began to take an
active part in resolving problems in the field of postal
operations. For example, it led a panel to resolve the issue of
terminal dues. It reflects that China has already has the ability
to contribute to resolving problems in international post aervice.
It also shows that China has won trust among both developed and
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
In November, 1972, China attended the annual meeting of the
Postal Study and Consultation Council of UPU in Bern.
</P>
<P>
Since then, China went through necessary procedures to approve
relevant conventions of UPU. It attended the UPU congresses from
1974 to 1994. It was elected as a vice-chairman of the UPU
congresses for four times and a member of the Postal Operation
Council at every congress. It was also elected as a member of the
Council of Administration at all but one of the UPU congresses. It
was also elected as vice-chairman of the Council of Administration
twice.
</P>
<P>
By the time when the 21st UPU Congress was held in Seoul in
1994, China had adopted all the existing conventions of UPU.
</P>
<P>
In January, 1994, China sent a letter to the International
Bureau of UPU to apply for hosting the 22nd UPU Congress in
Beijing. China's application was later approved at the 21st UPU
Congress in Seoul, which decided that the next congress will be
held in Beijing from August 23 to September 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the convention of UPU congress, China will be the
chairman of the coming UPU congress and the chairman of the
Council of Administration till the next UPU congress.
</P>
<P>
China has placed great importance on hosting the UPU congress.
Chinese President Jiang Zemin is the honorary chairman of the
Chinese Organizing Committee. Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo is
the chairman of the organizing committee. The organizing committee
consists officials from more than 20 ministries and government
departments.
</P>
<P>
China has made careful preparations for the UPU congress,
including construction of a new convention building. At present,
Beijing is ready to receive the more than 2,200 people from over
170 countries and over 30 international organizations to the UPU
congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enhances Trademark Protection for Overseas Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- China is taking measures to
combat trademark violations involving overseas companies in a bid
to protect their rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, the number of trademark infringement cases
has increased considerably, seriously harming the interests of
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released today by the State
Administration For Industry and Commerce, related departments in
China handled 713 trademark violation cases in the first half of
this year, a hefty annual increase of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 690 cases involved trademark abuses of overseas
companies, and the number of such cases was up more than 30
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the administration said that China will
further enhance efforts in fighting against violations of the
Trademark Law in the areas of production, circulation, printing,
and applications to protect the rights of overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
He said that China recently mapped out a priority list
protecting 280 famous domestic and overseas trademarks.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, industrial and commercial
administrations nationwide enhanced supervision of the production
and trading of fake products and the infringement of trademarks in
the commercial sector, and fined and punished a number of
violators.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities in the city of Shenzhen in south China's
Guangdong Province levied a heavy fine against the violator of
Japan's YKK company trademark, and in Xiamen, in southeast China,
those responsible were fined 40 percent of their annual revenue
for printing a famous Thailand beverage's trademark without
permission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Affairs Officials Meet in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A three-day national conference
attended by chiefs of provincial-level Taiwan affairs offices from
across the country concluded here today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Qian Qichen addressed the meeting, and
participants studied and discussed instructions from the central
leadership on the current campaign against the "two-state" remarks
made by Taiwan leader Lee Teng-hui in his July 9 speech.
</P>
<P>
The anti-separatist drive has won nationwide and worldwide
support, and has strongly shocked the island province. The
participants agreed that the struggle against Lee's "two-state"
remarks is of great importance for the sovereignty, territorial
integrity, and peaceful reunification of the country.
</P>
<P>
They held that Lee's "two-state" remarks are against the will
of the Chinese people, have met a cold shoulder internationally,
and are doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the importance of adhering to the basic
principle of "peaceful reunification, one country with two systems,
" they said that China can never commit itself to giving up the
use of force in reunifying the country.
</P>
<P>
The participants pledged to continue to promote personnel,
economic and cultural exchanges between the two sides across the
Taiwan Straits, and continue to encourage Taiwan businessmen to
invest in the mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
