<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Investigates Victims of U.S. Toxic Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has been investigating the
victims of toxic chemicals sprayed by U.S. army during the war in
Vietnam from 1961 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
An investigation conducted by the Department of Labor, War
Invalids and Social Affairs of Vietnam's central province of Lam
Dong shows that as many as 2,075 people of 974 households in the
province are victims of toxic chemicals sprayed by U.S. army
during the war in Vietnam, according to a report of Vietnam News
Agency (VNA) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The investigation on the consequences of U.S. toxic chemical
sprays further shows that 985 were directly affected by toxic
chemicals; 1,043 were born with deformities in the second
generation, and 47 others, the third generation.
</P>
<P>
The investigation also indicates that 715 such people are
unable to work and 404 totally paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
The investigation began in 1998 in Tay Ninh, Binh Duong and Ba
Ria-Vung Tau provinces in the south and Nam Dinh and Bac Ninh
provinces and Hai Phong city in the north.
</P>
<P>
It shows that there are 22,000 victims of U.S. Toxic Chemicals
in the five provinces and one city.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial reports released previously, VNA said,
between 1961 and 1971, U.S. aircraft sprayed 72 million liters of
toxic chemicals in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
When the war in Vietnam ended in 1975, 3 million Vietnamese had
been reportedly killed, 4.4 million wounded and 2 million affected
by toxic chemicals, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Picture Album of Xinjiang's Cultural Relics Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region has published a picture album which
systematically and comprehensively introduces the cultural relics
of the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference here today, officials of
the Xinjiang's Cultural Department and the Cultural Heritage
Bureau said this album is the region's gift to the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China on
October 1 and Macao's return to the motherland on December 20 of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The album contains over 1,000 photos of ancient cites, cultural
relics discovered in the region, and 12 research papers on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
Some of the pictures are relics unearthed in recent years and
never before seen by the public.
</P>
<P>
The album is a most authoritative text for readers to discover
Xinjiang's cultural heritage and the latest research in the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
