<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Raps U.S. for Stirring Up Arms Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) charged on Wednesday that the United
States stirred up an arms race in recent years through arms export,
posing a serious threat to peace and stability in the world.
</P>
<P>
The United States should first retrieve its military machinery
around the world before pointing its fingers at the DPRK's
satellite and missile program, said a DPRK Foreign Affairs
Ministry spokesman in an interview with the Korean Central News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman quoted a New York Times report as saying that the
United States was the biggest arms exporter last year with the
official arms sales amounting to 7.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He condemned the United States for using countries such as Iraq
and Yugoslavia as arms testing grounds to improve its mass
destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the United States recently raised a hue
and cry about the "threats" of DPRK's satellite and missile
program in order to find an excuse for attempting to repeat on the
Korean peninsula what it has done in Iraq and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the U.S. military threats could only
compel the DPRK to adopt such means as satellite and missile
launching to safeguard its sovereignty, peace and stability, and
try every possible way to enhance its national strength and
military power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
