<HEADLINE> Prime Suspect in Ship Killings Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The prime suspect in last year
's murder of 23 Chinese citizens aboard a Hong Kong-registered
ocean-going ship was detained by police on Sunday night in Huilai
County in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Information from the Guangdong Provincial Public Security
Bureau said that the prime suspect, Weng Siliang, along with Zhu
Youwang, another major suspect, collaborated with an international
pirate group led by an Indonesian in the ransacking of the cargo
ship.
</P>
<P>
The "Cheung Son" cargo ship, owned by Hong Kong Waibert
Steamship Co. Ltd, set sail from Shanghai on November 12, 1998,
bound for Malaysia. Twenty-three Chinese citizens were hired to
work as crew members aboard the ship.
</P>
<P>
The ship was stopped on the South China Sea on November 16 by a
group of people, including Weng, who were in shabby sheet metal
boats. The pirates killed all the Chinese crewmen aboard, and
took over the ship.
</P>
<P>
The dead bodies of the 23 missing crew members were later found
on the coast near Shanwei, Lufeng, and Huilai, all in Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese public security officers scoured 12 provinces and
municipalities and detained 54 other suspects, but Weng Siliang, a
resident of Shanwei, remained at large for a long time.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Weng's capture, Zhu Youliang was caught by police on
August 8. The killing of the 23 Chinese crewmen was the worst
crime on the high seas of China since the founding of the People's
Republic of China in October of 1949.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
