<HEADLINE> Uzbekistan Denies Bombing Targeted at Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Uzbek Air Force's bombing
on the militants based in Kyrgyzstan Sunday was not aimed in any
way at targets in Tajikistan, said Uzbek Foreign Minister
Abdulaziz Kamilov Tuesday in the Uzbek capital of Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
However, the possibility cannot be ruled out that the aircraft
flew into Tajikistan because the militants were in the border area
between Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, said Kamilov, according to
report monitored in Alma Ata.
</P>
<P>
The operation was conducted upon the request by Kyrgyzstan to
eliminate rebel forces, said Kamilov.
</P>
<P>
Uzbek Security Council secretary Morakbar Rakhmonkulov said
that the militants planned to continue into Uzbekistan to stage
diversions there.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan's national security chief Esen Topoyev has confirmed
that Uzbek warplanes hit targets in the southern mountainous area
some 15 kilometers from the Tajik border where the gunmen were
believed to be located, according to a separate report.
</P>
<P>
Tajik Foreign Minister Talbak Nazarov summoned on Monday Uzbek
Ambassador to Tajikistan, Bakhtiyar Urdashev, to protest the
bombing of its northern territory by Uzbek planes early Sunday
morning, and demanded steps be taken to prevent such events from
happening again.
</P>
<P>
The bombing caused no casualties but killed more than 100
cattle and ruined a lot of buildings and farmlands, according to
the Tajik Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
