<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians May Be Exposed to DU Hazard in Kosovo, MP Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Canadian troops in Kosovo may be
exposed to hazard caused by NATO's depleted uranium bombs, the
Globe and Mail newspaper Wednesday quoted a Reform MP as warning.
</P>
<P>
"We know how badly they have botched the handling of soldiers
exposed to bauxite and PCBs in Croatia and my concern is that we
are seeing a repeat of that experience," Reform MP Art Hanger said
Tuesday referring to the depleted uranium hazard.
</P>
<P>
The defense critic called on the Department of National Defense
to launch a thorough investigation to determine how much depleted
uranium is in the vicinity of Canadian troops in Kosovo, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The safety warning came after the release this week of about 1,
000 pages of Defense Department documents dealing with depleted
uranium, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"The hazards after firing are directly related to ingestion, or
ingress of particle through wounds," the documents said, adding "
an uneducated public, in close contact with areas subject to
concentrated attacks from DU would be at some health hazard."
</P>
<P>
The same documents, however, dismiss concerns about the
potentially damaging health effects of exposure to the DU
ammunition, saying: "DU is nothing more than metal byproduct of
the uranium refining process, "with only" slight levels of
radioactivity equal to that from a luminous wrist-watch dial for
each projectile."
</P>
<P>
During NATO's bombardment of Yugoslavia the alliance's fighter
jets had dropped scores of bombs containing depleted uranium in
order to force the Yugoslav army out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail newspaper said Canada will have about 1,300
peacekeepers serving in Kosovo and Macedonia by the end of this
month.
</P>
<P>
The UN Environment Program last week said it would conduct an
investigation to determine if there was health damage caused by DU
shells in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
