<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African Countries Take Measures to Curb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and other southern
African countries will introduce an international vehicle
clearance certificate to combat increased vehicle trafficking
across the borders, a police spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wayne Bvudzijena, officer of the Police Press and Public
Relations, said the certificate was expected to be in place by
January next year and would be obtainable from the police.
</P>
<P>
He said this decision was made by ministers responsible for
police operations at the Southern African Regional Police Chiefs
Cooperation Organization (SARPCCO) meeting held in Swaziland last
month.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers noted with concern the unacceptable high level
of organized transnational and violent crimes within the region
and appreciated the efforts to combat crime," he said.
</P>
<P>
Countries which were represented at the meeting include Angola,
Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The officer said the purpose of the certificate would be to
serve as proof that a vehicle was not reported stolen in a SARPCCO
country where it would be registered before being taken to another
country.
</P>
<P>
The clearance certificate would have unique security features
which would include a watermark that could only be read under
ultra violet light, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in 1997, during a police operation
involving Mozambique, Zambia, South Africa and Zimbabwe, 1,576
stolen vehicles were recovered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
