<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Improves Education in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Li Haifeng, motivated by the
trend toward open education and the idea of sharing educational
resources, decided to establish a school network for Beijing No.
101 Middle School, which was founded by the Communist Party of
China (CPC) in the caves of Yan'an, a base area of the Chinese
revolution.
</P>
<P>
No.101 School, one of Beijing's key middle schools, became the
first middle school in China to be linked to the Internet in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"People can easily find what we were teaching last week on the
'net," said Li, the school's headmaster, adding that "hundreds of
thousands of people have benefited from the Internet." No.101
School has set up more than 30 sub-centers in over two-thirds of
China's administrative regions.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Education said that the
creation of the school network is an important technological base
for providing a modern education.
</P>
<P>
"The adoption of school networking will help improve the
quality of education and be conducive to popularizing the
education designed to improve students' quality in China," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
China is now trying to link its primary and middle schools to
the Internet in a bid to enlarge the world for students and help
them become more creative.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education is now preparing to set up a special
databank within the school network, CERNET (China Education and
Research Network), and has already begun to collect excellent
design plans nationwide for the project. Designs which pass the
appraisal of experts will be recommended to schools across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education adopted the use of censorship in
recommending educational software to be used by primary and middle
schools, and only software passing the Ministry's examination will
be included on the list of recommended teaching and learning
materials for the schools.
</P>
<P>
According to incomplete statistics, school networks have been
established or are under construction in over 500 of China's 930,
000 primary and middle schools, with many more planning to do so.
School investment in the network ranged from hundreds of thousands
of yuan to over one million yuan (about 120,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The problems in the construction of school networks include an
over-emphasis on hardware rather than on appropriate software, and
some of the equipment has been used less than anticipated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Jailed for Evading, Resisting Court Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme People's Court (SPC)
said here today that seven people have been given jail terms
ranging from one year to 13 years for intentional evasion of or
violent resistance to the enforcement of court rulings.
</P>
<P>
These sentences are part of the country's week-long media
campaign against local interference with and resistance to the
enforcement of court rulings, which aims to eliminate
difficulties rooted in local protectionism.
</P>
<P>
"Those who dare to interfere in or resist the enforcement of
court rulings should be punished according to law, otherwise the
unity and dignity of the country's laws cannot be ensured," said
Li Guoguang, vice-president of the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Chen Guoan, a jobless man in southwest China's Yunnan Province,
threw a grenade at law enforcers while they were performing their
duties. Fortunately, the law officers jumped aside immediately and
narrowly escaped death.
</P>
<P>
Chen was sentenced 13 years for attempted homicide and
resistance to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of June, more than 850,000
court rulings involving 259 billion yuan (about 31.2 billion U.S.
dollars) had yet to be executed.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme People's Court has vowed to reform the current law
enforcement system, and plans to unify and coordinate law
enforcement units in order to eliminate problems related to the
enforcement of court rulings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
