<HEADLINE> Philippine President Concludes Visit to Brunei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada concluded Wednesday his two-day state visit to Brunei
aiming at boosting trade and bilateral ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release of the Presidential Palace issued
here, during the visit, the two countries agreed to create a joint
commission that would oversee trade relations between them.
</P>
<P>
"In my private talk with His Majesty, Sultan Haji Hassanal
Bolkiah, we agreed to study more about the trade relations between
our two countries because in the past years, it has declined and
we want to reinvigorate again," Estrada said through the release.
</P>
<P>
Estrada added that he expects Mindanao island, which the
Philippine government has pledged to transform into the country's
food provider and new economic hub, to benefit the most from the
agreements reached during the visit.
</P>
<P>
He noted the agreements include a deal for food production, as
well as the opening of daily flights between Brunei and Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The two governments pledged to promote and facilitate trade and
investments between them and encourage their respective business
sectors to enhance their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippines and Brunei also reiterated their
commitment to the development of the
Brunei-Indonesia-Malaysia-Philippines East ASEAN Growth Area and
strengthen their cooperation in the fields of education, human
resource development, defense and tourism.
</P>
<P>
This is Estrada's first visit to Brunei since he assumed
presidential office in June 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
