<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Breaks Up Drug Network in 14 U.S. Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. federal agents conducted
drug raids in 14 cities Tuesday, arresting scores of people and
seizing drugs and money, the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
announced.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to break up one of the top 20 drug distribution
networks in the country, the agents have seized 14 more kilograms
of cocaine, two Ferrari autos, a Land Rover and seven weapons,
including an AK-47 assault rifle, Assistant Director of Federal
Investigation Bureau (FBI) Thomas Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
By late Tuesday afternoon, 77 arrests were made, and more than
20 others were expected, FBI said.
</P>
<P>
The raids were carried out in New York City, Boston, Cleveland,
Chicago Atlanta, Dallas, Houston, Albany, New York, and Nashville,
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
Pickard said the raids called Operation Southwest Express
disrupted "a major drug trafficking organization from its
distribution system to its retail sales."
</P>
<P>
FBI has arrested Omar Rocha Soto, head of the San Diego-based
organization, and three bothers of the Sotello-Lopez family from
their El Paso, Texas base. They were charged with drug trafficking,
money laundering and conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
During a year-long investigation, agents seized 4,158 pounds of
marijuana, 2,727 kilograms of cocaine and more than 1.15 million
dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
The investigation was jointly conducted by the FBI, the Drug
Enforcement Administration, the Justice Department, Customs
Service, Internal Revenue Service and Immigration and
Naturalization Service. More than 50 state and local police
agencies also took part.
</P>
<P>
"This investigation has resulted in a major disruption of the
flow of drugs from the Southwest border throughout the United
States," said FBI Director Louis Freeh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
