<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Fraudulent Letters Rampant in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria continues to top the list
of letter fraud and related cases in the United States, making its
citizens prime suspects of crime in most parts of their host
cities, a local newspaper said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Postal Service said in a statement recently that it is
making efforts "to halt a scheme that relies upon international
mail to send letters offering fraudulent business proposals to
American addresses."
</P>
<P>
It added that postal inspectors have been cheated out of
nearly 100 million US dollars annually. Inspectors have
confiscated over four million fraudulent letters since March 1998,
 said the Guardian, a leading Nigerian paper.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the statement as saying that Americans are not
the only ones targeted, adding: "Letters also show up in Europe
and the Pacific Rim".
</P>
<P>
But the statement praised Nigerian postal authorities, saying
with their help "inspection service officials in the New York
division have developed a profile of letters and packages that may
be linked to the scam."
</P>
<P>
The statement explained that since U. S. postal inspectors have
seized over four million such letters in recent years, "the people
behind this scheme are trying something new".
</P>
<P>
Specifically, it said that "some letters now arrive in bulk
packaging via private courier". Once such packages are in the
U.S., it stated, "they are broken down to single letters, affixed
with U.S. postage or no postage and sent to other countries
bearing an American return address to disguise its west African
origin".
</P>
<P>
Many of such mails, about 2.3 million mainly coming from Lagos
and suspected to be fraudulent were reportedly packed together
and dumped last year in a landfill in Long Island, New York.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, U.S. federal investigators contend that
the Nigeria-U.S. axis mail fraud are part of what has been
described as "the oldest mail fraud scheme" in America dating
back to the 60s.
</P>
<P>
Under the defunct (Abdulsalam) Abubakar regime, the Central
Bank of Nigeria last October had placed advertisements in major
western papers, including the New York Times, warning Americans
and Europeans about the danger of such fraudulent letters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
