<HEADLINE> Dozen People Injured in Australia's Trains Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Around a dozen people were
injured Wednesday when a passenger train collided with a freight
train about 200 kilometers east of Kalgoorlie in the south of the
Western Australian (WA) state, police said.
</P>
<P>
The train of the Indian Pacific train service, carrying about
170 passengers, collided at low speed with a stationary freight
train Wednesday afternoon, cutting Australia's only east-west rail
link.
</P>
<P>
Australian police and the Royal Flying Doctor Service (RFDS)
said there were no major injuries with one RFDS plane carrying a
doctor already near the scene and another two on their way.
</P>
<P>
A RFDS spokesman said the train had been derailed.
</P>
<P>
"It has been derailed, and about 11 people will need RFDS
transport," he said.
</P>
<P>
But none of the injuries were believed to be serious, he added.
</P>
<P>
WA police inspector Alf Fordham said the Indian Pacific had
been traveling west on the trans-continental line at the time of
the crash.
</P>
<P>
National Rail spokesman Fred Affleck said there appeared to be
minimal damage to the trains and the track.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Pacific is a trans-continental train service,
linking Perth and Sydney via Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
The 4,352-kilometer journey takes two and a half days.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Pacific was formerly owned by Australian National
Railways but sold to the Great Southern Railway consortium in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
