<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yajia, Pulling Contest Between Elephants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nicknamed "pulling contest between
elephants", it isn't a zoo show. It's a traditional ethnic sport
formally called Yajia.
</P>
<P>
It's very much like the tug-of-war, in which two men or two
groups in the same category of weight try to pull each other and
one will be the winner if the stripe tied to the middle of the
solid band moves beyond the win-loss line in his direction.
</P>
<P>
But the two contestants will not use their hands but necks
which are hitched to the band by a hoop on each side, and they
need to straddle the band and squat down before they begin the
pulling contest.
</P>
<P>
Is it dangerous to use their neck instead of hands?
</P>
<P>
Li Mingzhao, the athlete with the Beijing delegation, said that
it is a safe sport because the band gets through between the legs.
</P>
<P>
"Without getting the band through between the legs, the neck is
in danger of being twisted after the band is stretched. Put the
tape through the legs can make sure the neck won't be injured," Li
said.
</P>
<P>
"And the hoop around the neck are cushioned with sponge which
will protect the neck from injury." he added.
</P>
<P>
A Tibetan athlete who studies in the Beijing Sports University
pointed out that the player is hard to win only dependent on the
neck.
</P>
<P>
"You are expected to put in action not only your neck but every
part of your body. For instance the force of the waist is also
very important in securing victory. In one word you need to put
all your body parts in concerted efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Duoji, deputy chief umpire, said that simple as it looks like,
Yajia is actually a competition not only of power but also
strategy.
</P>
<P>
"It is simple so there are so many spectators here, unlike the
top-whipping event which is hard to be taken in by the laymen. "
</P>
<P>
"But it is not only the competition of power, but also the
strategy. For example, some athletes do not exert fully his force
but just stay put until his opponent exhaust his force, then he
will explode to pull the tired opponent beyond."
</P>
<P>
"It can also test your psyche. The athlete need to be persevere
enough if he wants to make a comeback triumph."
</P>
<P>
The pulling contest, which has attracted a large number of
locals whether old or young, women or men, has upgraded from the
exhibition to competitive event.
</P>
<P>
"It originated from the daily life of the Tibetans, but it has
won popularity with the other ethnic groups, so it became the
competitive event in this games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Create National Population Information Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua)-- China plans to create a
population information network among 133 cities by the end of this
year, and build a national population information network within
three years, the Ministry of Public Security said here today.
</P>
<P>
The future network is expected to provide police units
nationwide with personal data on all citizens above the age of 16,
which will be aid local police in keeping track of the floating
population.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the national information network will not
only modernize the management system of household registration,
but will also improve cooperation among police units nationwide,"
said a senior police officer with the ministry.
</P>
<P>
"But, first of all, the network will benefit economic
development," the officer said, explaining that it will prevent
criminals from using fake ID cards to apply for credit cards.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the national network also will give the
police access to the ID card number and picture of every citizen,
"as a result, criminals will have no opportunities," he said.
</P>
<P>
China began to manage population information with computers in
1985 in Jilin City in northeast China's Jilin Province, and by
1988, more than 500 cities nationwide had adopted the practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
