<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has sent a high-level
delegation to Dushanbe, Tajikistan for talks with Afghan
opposition in a move to restore the peace process of Afghanistan,
said an official press release here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani delegation consisting of Secretary of Interior
Rustam Shah and Pakistan's ambassador in Kabul Aziz Ahmad Khan is
currently holding talks with an Afghan opposition team headed by
Younis Qanooni, a close aide to opposition commander Ahmad Shah
Masood.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani team is expected to return to Islamabad on
Thursday and Afghanistan's ruling Taliban militia's leadership
will be briefed on the details of the Dushanbe meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani delegation will proceed to Kandahar, the
stronghold of the Taliban in southern Afghanistan on August 21
where they will call on the supreme Taliban leader Mulla Omar,
said the press release.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is alleged to have been supporting the Taliban in
their recent offensive against the opposition and Masood accused
Pakistan of sending troops into Taliban's ranks.
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistan has repeatedly rejected such accusations and
said it has consistently been for the restoration of durable peace
in Afghanistan through negotiations and dialogue. 
