<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan Won't Be Saved by Foreign Powers, Newspaper (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is not incidental that Lee made his "two states" remark, the
commentary says. Lee has been deliberately planning to split the
motherland for a long time. Only recently did he sniff out some
seemingly favorable conditions, and then he brazenly tossed off
the statement.
</P>
<P>
This year's incidents such as NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia, the
U.S. attacks on the Chinese embassy in Belgrade and the passing of
the new Japan-U.S. Defense Cooperation Guideline made Lee believe
that the time for realizing his scheme had arrived.
</P>
<P>
So, Lee lost no time in putting forward his "two states" remark,
with the hope that foreign powers would lend him a big hand in his
efforts to separate Taiwan from the motherland, the commentary
says.
</P>
<P>
However, Lee cannot expect to be saved by foreign powers, it
stresses.
</P>
<P>
Lee has made a miscalculation of the major tendency in the
world. He saw only the support of a small number of foreigners,
but not the fact that the majority of countries recognize that
there is only one China, and Taiwan is part of China.
</P>
<P>
After Lee's "two states" remark, nearly 100 countries,
including the United States and Japan, swiftly reiterated their
adherence to the "One China" principle, and much of the world
media reproached Lee for his provocative behavior.
</P>
<P>
All this has demonstrated that the current situation is not as
rosy as Lee had thought, and that there are few foreigners
supporting Lee, the commentary says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Protect Intellectual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- African governments have been
advised to develop sustainable networks for future utilization of
trade-related aspects of intellectual property rights and other
aspects of intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Justice Minister Mayanja Nkangi said in a speech read
by a senior legal officer here Wednesday that the networks would
be tools for technological, economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The minister assured the World International Property
Organization (WIPO) of Uganda's full support for all efforts being
directed toward the promotion of intellectual property rights
between agencies in Uganda and the region as well as the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a two-week course attended by the participants from
15 African countries, Edward Kwakwa, a WIPO representative, said
that the course is part of the process to raise awareness about
aspects of international property rights in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The organization will enhance cooperation in legal technical
assistance for developing countries to strengthen national policy
and legislative frameworks and to build capacity for implementing
the agreement on property rights.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the World Trade Organization, the
Organization of African Unity and the South African Development
Community are also attending the course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
