<HEADLINE> Lee Tung-hui of Taiwan Won't Be Saved by Foreign Powers, Newspaper (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the international community, there exist some forces that
support Lee's separatist attempts. However, when and to what
extend Lee will be supported, will be determined by their own
interests. Hoping for unconditional foreign support is simply the
wishful thinking of Lee himself, it says.
</P>
<P>
Lee has created a new crisis across the Taiwan Straits, and
brought turbulence to the entire Asian Pacific Region. It is quite
natural that Lee has been deemed "a troublemaker" by the
international community. "This has put Lee's reliance on foreign
powers at a discount," it says.
</P>
<P>
Lee cannot expect to be saved by foreign powers, since the
issue of Taiwan is China's internal affair which brooks no foreign
intervention, the commentary points out.
</P>
<P>
Lee's attempts to solicit foreign powers into interfering with
China's internal affairs have aroused the strong opposition of the
Chinese nation and the censure of the world media. "A just cause
enjoys abundant support, while an unjust cause finds little
support. Lee is doomed to failure," it says.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that no country will disregard legal principles,
morality and justice, be an enemy of the entire Chinese people,
and stake everything on a single throw, just for Lee's personal
ambition," the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
It reiterates that China's affairs should be solved by the
Chinese people themselves, especially major issues of principle,
such as national integrity and unity. "Those relying on foreign
powers have never come to a good end," the commentary notes.
</P>
<P>
"Now that Lee wants to follow in their footsteps, he is
destined to come to a disgraceful end and stand condemned through
the ages," it concludes. 
