<HEADLINE> Chinese Expedition Warned of Polar Bears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, August 18 (Xinhua)-- The Chinese scientists
aboard the icebreaker Snow Dragon worried the final-phase of the
Arctic expedition might be affected by polar bears.
</P>
<P>
The expedition ship again encountered the snow-white
inhabitants of the Arctic Ocean early this morning while sailing
slowly in a floating-ice area.
</P>
<P>
Frequent appearance of the polar bears has brought anxiety
rather than excitement to the expedition members, who plan to set
up a working station on a piece of ice today to conduct the week-
long observation and research.
</P>
<P>
"Polar bears may impose difficulties to scientific research,
and every team member should be very careful about the safety,"
warned chief scientist Chen Liqi, who led the expedition team.
</P>
<P>
Around-the-clock patrols have been arranged to protect
scientists. Shooting is permitted only when the bear is 100 meters
close to attack man.
</P>
<P>
Xia Xinmin, who is in charge of the patrol, said they will try
their best not to hurt polar bears while ensuring the safety of
the scientists.
</P>
<P>
Polar bear is among the largest beasts on the earth. Living in
the Arctic region, it runs even faster than man.  
</P>
</TEXT>
