<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Asks Egypt to Explain Airspace Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy summoned Egypt's Ambassador to Israel Mohamed Bassiouny
Wednesday, asking him to explain why Egypt refused to allow an
Israeli passenger plane to pass through its airspace.
</P>
<P>
A Boeing 747 with 329 passengers had to return to Tel Aviv
Tuesday night after air-controllers in Egypt denied it permission
to enter Egyptian airspace on its route to Bangkok, Israel Radio
said.
</P>
<P>
It was the third such incident involving Israeli aircraft in
the last 10 days, the radio said. Two charter planes to Kenya were
also denied permission to enter Egyptian airspace.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of the Foreign Ministry Eitan Bentsur met
Bassiouny Tuesday to express Israeli concerns over the incidents,
and the ambassador promised that the Egyptian government would
make a thorough investigation, officials with Israeli Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted Abdel Fatah Tutwul, head of Egypt's Civil
Aviation Authority, as saying that Israel had failed on occasion
to request permission to use Egyptian airspace.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel signed a peace treaty with Egypt in 1979, all
flights from Tel Aviv to Bangkok, Bombay, South Africa and Kenya
have passed over the Sinai Peninsula in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
