<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firm Fined for Stock Market Manipulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- An investment firm in the city
of Xi'an in Shaanxi Province will be fined for manipulating
securities investment-fund prices, a press official at the China
Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC) confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
An earlier decision of the CSRC said the Xi'an Hangbiao
Investment Consultative Company was warned, fined two million yuan,
and have the 61.1 million yuan it gained by manipulation
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Its manager Zhao Wenliang, was also warned and fined 200,000
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The CSRC found that from April 8, 1998 to June 4, 1998, the
company spent 100 million yuan through 104 private accounts to
increase its holding in the Seagull Securities Investment Fund
from 4.54 million shares to 37.24 million shares, accounting for
74 percent of the fund's total shares.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the company used accounts under its control
for speculative trading so that the fund's price rose from two
yuan a share on April 8, 1998 to 5.99 yuan on June 9, 1998.
</P>
<P>
By July 21, 1998 when the company sold all its holdings, it had
earned a total of 61.1 million yuan, the CSRC said.
</P>
<P>
The CSRC decided that the company had violated regulations on
the prevention of securities manipulation and must, therefore, be
punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
