<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Advertising Business Volume Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- China's advertising business
volume hit 25 billion yuan (about three billion U.S. dollars) in
the first half of this year, up 15.5 percent from the
corresponding period of last year, sources from the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce said here today.
</P>
<P>
The top five categories of advertisement with the most sales
volume are those of household electrical appliances, food and
beverage, medicines, cosmetics and real estate.
</P>
<P>
Advertisements of medical services saw the fastest annual
increase of 27.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Shanghai and Guangdong Province continued to lead the
country in advertising business with their sales volume accounting
for more than one half of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Industrial and commercial departments at various levels
conducted thorough qualification examinations of advertising
agencies this year to standardize the advertising market, and
revoked the licenses of a number of sub-standard advertising units,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the number of advertising units and employees
Chinawide dropped 5 percent and 5.4 percent, respectively,
compared with the figures of 1998.
</P>
<P>
China had 58,642 advertising units, with 547,633 employees by
June this year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Radio stations and newspapers all witnessed a hefty drop in the
number of employees in their advertising departments as compared
with last year, while the people working for television stations'
advertising departments increased.
</P>
<P>
China's advertising business volume exceeded 50 billion yuan in
1998, up 16.4 percent from the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
