<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Develops Electron Accelerator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian Bhabha Atomic Research
Center (BARC) is reportedly in the final stages of assembling a
powerful electron accelerating machine, which can potentially be
used as a beam weapon.
</P>
<P>
The machine, developed by Mumbai-based BARC, would be ready for
testing by the end of the year, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
When aimed at enemy missiles and aircraft, Indian scientists
claimed, bursts of microwaves packed with gigawatts of power
produced by this machine, named "KALI-5000," would cripple their
electronics systems and computer chips and bring them down.
</P>
<P>
However, India's beam weapon in the present form was too bulky
with a weight of 26 tons including tanks containing 12,000 liters
of oil, PTI said, quoting P. H. Ron, head of the accelerator and
pulse power division at BACR and KALI's chief designer.
</P>
<P>
KALI, kilo-ampere linear injector, was developed for industrial
applications and that the defense use was a recent spin-off,
according to Ron.
</P>
<P>
Development of KALI machine, described as India's first star
war weapon, was initiated in 1985 by then BARC director
Rajagopalam Chidambaram, now chairman of India's Atomic Energy
Commission, but work began earnestly in 1989.
</P>
<P>
BARC scientists claimed that the KALI machine has for the first
time provided India with a way to "harden" the electronic systems
used in satellites and missiles against the deadly electromagnetic
impulses generated by nuclear weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
