<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Release Ozone Monitoring Balloons in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- An expedition team consisting of
Chinese and Japanese scientists released high-altitude balloons in
Lhasa, capital of Tibet Autonomous Region Wednesday, to monitor
ozone layer and collect atmospheric data.
</P>
<P>
The team has used a laser radar to monitor the vertical
distribution of ozone in atmosphere above the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, known as the "Roof of the World." The data will be used
for the research of the thinner ozone layer above the plateau in
summer time.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the research will be beneficial to studies on the
reduction of ozone in stratosphere and on the climatic and
environmental changes on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The scientific expedition in Tibet, which was jointly sponsored
by the National Committee of the Natural Sciences Fund and the
Greencool Company, will last for about one month. It involves
scientists from the Institute of Atmospheric Physics under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences and Nagoya University in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
