<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Cut More Than Third of Its Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to trim 30,000 of armed
forces so as to make its army more compact and better equipped,
said the country's Defense Minister Theophilus Danjuma.
</P>
<P>
Danjuma said that the new Nigerian armed forces will be "fully
professionalized, better equipped and completely subordinated to
civil political authority," the Guardian newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria currently has an 80,000-strong armed forces and the
planned trimming would cut across the Army, Navy, and Air Force,
to reduce the figure to 50,000, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
While describing it commendable, the minister, rumored to have
resigned at the weekend, said the continuing dominance by Nigeria
in the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) will not be in
the country's long-term interest because of its enormous cost
compared with other competing needs for resources at home.
</P>
<P>
Danjuma called on the international community, particularly the
 United States, to assist in demobilizing the men, through
training for self- employment.
</P>
<P>
He also advocates training of the personnel in service, saying
Nigeria would appreciate placement of its officers in foreign
military institutions, particularly in schools of armory,
artillery, signals and infantry. This becomes imperative because
the corps schools in Nigeria need to be refurbished, and their
equipment rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
The minister, a former Chief of Army Staff, decried the state of
 the Air Force fleet, saying that of the eight C-130 Hercules
aircraft, only one is serviceable.
</P>
<P>
On June 11, an unprecedented gale of retirement was unleashed on
the military and police by the new administration of President
Olusegun Obasanjo, making a clean sweep of officers who had held
political offices from 1985 to date.
</P>
<P>
A total of 93 officers were affected in the purge which
government spokesman Doyin Okupe described as part of
"far-reaching measures that will ensure permanent subordination
of the military to civil authority".
</P>
<P>
The measures were a "painful decision", but also "a
necessity," he added.
</P>
<P>
The history of the Nigerian Army dates back to 1897 with the
formation of West Africa Frontier Force (WAFF) by Frederic Lugard.
</P>
<P>
By 1941, military units were formed with a total of 250 men. By
1960 when the country attained its independence, there were 10,000
soldiers. The population grew to 250,000 in 1970 at the end of
the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
