<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Changes Attract World's Attention: Greek CP Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- General Secretary of the
Communist Party of Greece (KKE) Aleka Papariga praised China's
progress made over the past five decades, saying the great changes
have made China a focus of world attention.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, she said many profound
changes have taken place in China since the founding of the People
's Republic of China in 1949, especially from 1978 when the late
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping initiated the opening-up and reform
policy.
</P>
<P>
"China is no longer the semi-feudal and semi-colonial country
it used to be before 1949, but one that is developing rapidly, so
much that it has become a center of analysts' attention," she said.
</P>
<P>
The general secretary described the rapid development in China
as "not casual," saying that it was the opening-up and reform
policy that had led to the significant progress in China,
especially in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
She believed that China's steady growth will undoubtedly
benefit both Asia and the whole world.
</P>
<P>
"When we speak about China's international status and role, we
are keeping in mind a country with one-fourth of the world's
population. Without this one-fourth, we cannot talk about world
security and peace, or even about the world at all," she said,
adding that China has a very active role to play and that efforts
to prevent it from doing so are doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
Papariga expressed the hope that China would strengthen its
ties with European countries in order to promote principles
leading to a more equitable international economic order, peace,
non-intervention into the internal affairs of other countries
under various pretexts, such as human rights and ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
She is confident that China will have a brighter future,
adding that as far as prospects are concerned, its developing
momentum will clearly be maintained.
</P>
<P>
She added that China is showing a robust growing tendency at a
time when Southeast Asia is facing financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Papariga also hoped for strengthened ties between the KKE and
the Communist Party of China (CPC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
