<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Warns Against Epidemics in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (
WHO) warned Wednesday that there is an urgent need to rebuild
public health systems capable of containing the spread of
communicable diseases in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, one case of suspected polio, 24 cases of
suspected Hepatitis A and one case of hemorrhagic fever have been
registered in Kosovo, Yugoslavia, according to WHO.
</P>
<P>
"These are the first cases registered in Kosovo" since the end
of the NATO bombing against Yugoslavia, WHO said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
The suspected polio case was detected in the Pristina Hospital
on August 11. The three-year-old boy lives in a deprived urban
area and has not been vaccinated against polio.
</P>
<P>
The 24 cases of jaundice were admitted to the Pristina Hospital
between August 4 and 11 with suspected Hepatitis A, and a 19-year-
old woman has been diagnosed as suffering from hemorrhagic fever,
according to WHO.
</P>
<P>
WHO is said to have been working since the end of the NATO
bombing to re-establish Kosovo's communicable disease surveillance
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
