<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Chief Laments Crime Upsurge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Inspector-General of
Police Alhaji Musiliu Smith has lamented that the police force in
the country had been tasked by myriad of problems and events in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with retired police inspectors general held
Tuesday in capital Abuja, he said that in the northeastern and
northwestern parts of the country, "armed bandits from
neighboring countries have made life unbearable for the
inhabitants to the extent that commercial and social activities
are almost grounded to a halt," the New Nigerian newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"In the western and eastern states, waves of armed robbery and
unsolved murder cases are increasing on daily basis," Smith said.
</P>
<P>
The inspector-general complained of a phenomenal rise in the
incidence of communal, ethnic and religious clashes in some parts
of the country, some of which, he said, had become an endless
crises.
</P>
<P>
He lamented the enormous challenges of policing the country in
a democratic setting and advised the police to concentrate more on
its major constitutional duties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Lagos State Governor, Senator Bola Ahmed Tinubu,
Tuesday linked the recent increase in crime rate in the state to
the activities of enemies of democracy who were determined to
sabotage the new democratic settings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
