<HEADLINE> EU To Provide Aid For Turkey Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
going to provide a first package of humanitarian aid for victims
of the earthquake that hit Turkey on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, said on
Wednesday that it had cleared the aid package worth of two million
euros (2.1 million U.S. dollars) as the first emergency step for
helping the victims in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive's humanitarian office will manage the aid in
close cooperation with the Turkish Red Crescent. Under EU's
arrangement, the "immediate relief supplies" will be handed to the
worst affected areas by the International Federation of the Red
Cross and Red Crescent (IFRC).
</P>
<P>
The funds will also be allocated to other partners of non-
governmental organizations "as the situation evolves and emergency
teams are being sent to the region," the Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake is described as the worst since the 1976 quake
in Tangshan, China.
</P>
<P>
The death toll has risen to at least 3,000 with rescue workers
still searching for survivors. Initial international relief
efforts are focused on search and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission predicts that the need for relief
supplies, such as food, medical care, tents, blankets and mobile
kitchens, will grow over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive said it is closely monitoring the situation in
Turkey in order to prepare further necessary aid for the victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
