<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Food Act Expected to Boost Thai Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A new food act, to be passed
within this year, will help increase competitiveness of Thai food
exporters and upgrade Thai food products to the international
standards, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new act, food origins must be traceable in the event
of irregularities and exporters would face penalties for
misleading and exaggerated advertisements, the official news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Food manufacturers and exporters would need to inform the Food
and Drug Administration (FDA) of their plans of improving quality
and standards, and apply for export permissions, rather than
proceeding with piles of paper work to authorities previously
concerned with export permissions, FDA Secretary-General Mongkol
Na Songkhla was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite the new challenges in keeping up with changing rules
and international demands, Thai food exporters are reported to
welcome the new law as it would give them more flexibility and
freedom from bureaucratic red tape that had dragged on their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The new act comes at a time when the Thai government has
announced a set target of 5 percent export growth target for next
year.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Thai Chamber of Commerce Viroj
Amatakulchai said that it was highly likely that the targeted
export growth would be achieved, as the government's latest
stimulus package on August 10 would bear good fruits next year.
</P>
<P>
But he was not sure whether this year's export target of 4
percent growth will be achieved.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months this year, Thailand's exports were at
31.9 billion U.S. dollars, leaving each of the rest five months
with a 4.9 billion dollar target in order to achieve the projected
56.4 billion dollars for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports here said that the International Monetary
Fund is likely to raise Thailand's export growth forecast for 1999
from 2 percent to 3.5 percent due to the improvement of Thailand's
exports in the first seven months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
