<HEADLINE> UNITA Militants Become POWs in Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Seven militants from the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) became
prisoners of war (POWs) in the southern neighboring country of
Namibia, local newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
UNITA militants were apprehended by the Namibian government
troops during a counter-attack against the separatist Liberation
Army of Caprivi, which has mounted a series of assaults on
government facilities since August 2 in the northeast strip of the
territory called Caprivi Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian military has not yet decided how to deal with the
POWs from the UNITA movement led by Jonas Savimbi, said Martin
Shalli, chief general- staff of the Namibian Army.
</P>
<P>
"The secessionists have no more money for basic necessities,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made Tuesday in Maputo, capital of Mozambique, at
the meeting of the Southern African Development Community (SADC),
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos warned his counterparts
against the incursion of UNITA troops into Namibia and the
Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that up to now, the separatists, who fight for
the break- away of Caprivi from Namibia, have been defeated and
repelled by the Namibian government troops and fled to neighboring
countries of Angola and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said that the Angolan and Zambian
 governments had promised to help pursue the Namibian separatist
militants.
</P>
<P>
Caprivi Strip, a 400-kilometers-long strip south to Angola and
north to Botswana, is an impoverished area in Namibia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
