<HEADLINE> Iran's New Judiciary Chief Promises Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's new judiciary chief
Ayatollah Seyyed Mohmoud Hashemi Shahroudi Wednesday promised
the judiciary, a conservative power organ, will be more
cooperative than before with the moderate government headed by
President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
"As you are following the program of political development, it
is necessary for the judiciary to pursue a judicial development as
well, because part of political success depends on judicial
development," Hashemi said when Khatami called on him at his
office to extend congratulations.
</P>
<P>
The two expressed willingness to cooperate in order to solve
the country's problems in a better way.
</P>
<P>
Hashemi was appointed by supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
on August 14 to succeed Mohammad Yazdi, whose two five-year terms
ended on the day.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi, a hard line conservative, was furiously attacked by the
moderate faction for factionalism in the legal field by putting
reformist officials behind bars and shutting down pro-Khatami
newspapers. Hashemi, however, is believed to be a
conservative-prone, but relatively neutral figure.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said Hashemi's presence in the judiciary was
"inspiring" because he wanted to "render services and introduce
reforms." "Your character encourages all pundits and jurists to
work with you, and this is a matter of hope for the government,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's moderate government had been at odds with other
power organs such as the Majlis (parliament) and the judiciary,
controlled by the conservative faction.
</P>
<P>
When Hashemi was introduced to the new post Tuesday, he said
the judiciary will not engage in factionalism, apparently in an
attempt to appease moderates' doubt about his future performance.
</P>
<P>
Four days ago, Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance
Ataollah Mohajerani said at a press conference that he hoped
under the leadership of Hashemi, no pro-reform newspapers will be
banned by the judiciary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
