<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UPU Chief: Beijing Congress to Open New Page in Global Postal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The 22nd Congress of the
Universal Postal Union (UPU) to be held in Beijing from August 23
to September 15 is an extremely important event for the postal
community worldwide at the turn of the century when postal
services face many new challenges, the UPU chief has said.
</P>
<P>
The major event that happens every five years "obviously is an
important moment for the UPU for two reasons", UPU Director
General Thomas Leavey told Xinhua in an exclusive interview at the
UPU headquarters in the Swiss capital of Berne before he left for
Beijing to attend the congress. so far, more than 2,200 people
from 170 countries and 31 international organizations have entered
their names as intended participants.
</P>
<P>
"First of all, China itself is a very important member of the
UPU, the world's most populous country with enormous growth
potential," Leavey said.
</P>
<P>
The key role that China plays in international relations, being
a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council, also
adds a lot of weight to the congress, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will lead the UPU to the 21st century as China will
chairman of the UPU's ruling Council of Administration for the
next five years, Leavey said.
</P>
<P>
"The second reason is the issues that are important in postal
policy," the UPU chief said. "We have a lot of changes that are
taking place in the postal world."
</P>
<P>
"There are movements toward deregulation, and liberalization of
postal services in many countries, which means that the postal
service which formerly was a governmental service is being more
and more considered as a commercial service, open to competition
by private sector firms," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the challenges the postal service is facing,
Leavey, an American, made a comparison between the Beijing
congress in 1999 and the Washington congress at the end of the
19th century when China formally joined the UPU.
</P>
<P>
"As the people in Washington in 1897 looked to the turn of the
century, they had a lot of challenges. As we look to the new
century now in Beijing, we also have many challenges," he said.
</P>
<P>
"At that time, for example, there was a perceived threat to
postal volume by telegraph and the new invention of telephone," he
said. "Today some people see a threat to postal volume because of
new technologies of Internet and electronic mail."
</P>
<P>
The UPU director General said that he is very confident that
the 189 UPU members will meet the challenges bravely and develop
the postal services in various ways.
</P>
<P>
"Now we, of course, need to adjust to technological
developments. And we are not pessimistic that physical mail will
completely disappear," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, he said, a recent UPU study shows there
will be moderate growth in physical mail of about three percent a
year on average throughout the world up to the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
"The growth rate in China, however, is much higher, estimated
between 9 to 10 percent a year. As China develops and continues to
develop," postal services in China will develop rapidly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Leavey said that, with the tremendous work done by the Chinese
in preparing the 22nd Universal Postal Congress, he believed the
congress in Beijing will be a great success and open a new page in
the UPU history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
