<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Housebuyers Using Internet Save Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Consumers in the United
States using Internet spend half the time in identifying and
purchasing a house compared to traditional buyers, according to a
survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Internet buyers are likely to spend two and a half months from
selecting a realtor to their house purchase decision, compared to
an average of five months spent by traditional buyers, said the
California Association of Realtors, which conducted the survey in
the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Compared to traditional buyers, the association said, Internet
buyers spend half the time -- a median period of four weeks,
looking for a house with an agent prior to purchase. They preview
and visit only four houses, compared to eight for traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of Internet buyers surveyed agreed that
Internet helped them in the buying process. Most of them said
Internet gave them help in dealing and selecting the location with
the best possible neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
While all traditional buyers drive around and preview houses
and neighborhood, only half of Internet buyers do so. 16 percent
of Internet buyers use newspaper advertising, compared with 76
percent of traditional buyers.
</P>
<P>
Internet buyers said their realtors used such technological
tools as e-mail, Web sites and listing on Internet.
</P>
<P>
On average, Internet buyers visited six Web sites to find a
realtor or broker, used eight Web sites to get listing information
and two sites to get mortgage information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
