<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Laos agree to Delay Railway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Thailand and
Laos have agreed to postpone the two country's first railway
network until the regional economic crisis is over, an advisor of
the contractor said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gun Nagamati, advisor of Pacific Transportation Co., was quoted
by Thailand News Agency as saying that his company discussed the
problem with the Lao government on August 10 and the latter agreed
to an indefinite delay due to the economic crunch.
</P>
<P>
The company's representatives informed the Lao authorities that
their partners and creditors prefer the delay because the demand
for railway service has declined by as much as 40 percent from
earlier expectations, Gun said.
</P>
<P>
Pacific Transportation has also proposed to reduce its stake in
the railway project from 75 percent if the Lao government can find
other partners to help implement it.
</P>
<P>
However, Gun confirmed that his company would not abandon the
project and believed the Lao government would not revoke the
contract due to the delay.
</P>
<P>
The company was granted a concession by the Lao government last
year to build a 1,000-kilometer railway network. The project was
supposed to start with a 14-kilometer railway line, estimated at
32 million U.S. dollars, from Vientiane across the Mekong river on
the Thai-Lao friendship bridge to the northeastern gateway
province of Nong Khai in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
