<HEADLINE> Ugandan, Rwandan Presidents to Attend SADC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan and Rwandan presidents
were expected to arrive in Maputo later Wednesday to attend the
on-going summit of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC).
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican presidential deputy press secretary Estefanio
Muhulove told Xinhua that the two presidents would join the SADC
leaders to discuss peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to say whether the two leaders would come here
to sign a cease-fire agreed upon between the two sides on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda are backing different factions fighting in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) by dispatching troops
to the war- torn country. Uganda President Yoweri Museveni and
Rwandan Vice President and Minister of Defense Paul Kagame agreed
to a cease-fire between their troops on Tuesday after marathon
talks.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reaffirmed their commitment to cooperating with
the verification teams from Zambia and South Africa and seeking a
peaceful resolution of the conflict in the DRC on the basis of the
Lusaka ceasefire accord signed on July 10 by six relevant African
states.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda are not SADC members. Their participation in
the summit would show the two countries' willingness to end
fighting in the DRC, SADC officials said. 
</P>
