<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Singapore's New President S.R. Nathan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Singapore ambassador-at-large
S. R. Nathan Wednesday was declared the country's second elected
president.
</P>
<P>
Nathan, 75 and a veteran civil servant and head of the
Institute of Defense and Strategic Studies, will be sworn in as
president of the Republic of Singapore on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Born to an Indian family in Singapore on July 3, 1924, Nathan
started his working life as an office boy at the age of 16 in an
architectural firm.
</P>
<P>
During the Japanese occupation, he learned Japanese and became
an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
Later he got a diploma in social studies and became a social
worker in the government service where he worked with unions to
help workers settle their grievances.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 28, he entered the University of Malaya in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
He was seconded from the civil service to the National Trades
Union Congress (NTUC) to help set up a research unit in 1962, the
year the NTUC was formed.
</P>
<P>
He was also involved in industrial relations work and was a
founder of the Pioneer Industries Employees Union in the 1960s and
was president of the Amalgamated Union of Public Employees
</P>
<P>
Nathan remained there till 1966 when he began his career to
serve in the defense and foreign affairs fields.
</P>
<P>
Nathan gained corporate experience when he was executive
chairman of the English newspaper, the Straits Times, Press Group,
from 1982 to 1988. Then he became Singapore's High Commissioner to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed ambassador to the United States in 1990.
</P>
<P>
After returning from his U.S. post in 1996, the veteran
diplomat, described by friends as affable and politically astute,
was given the job of starting and steering the Institute of
Defense and Strategic Studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
