<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Base Lending Rate Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- All banks in Kenya have raised
their base lending rates to 18 percent and above, with the range
of their lending rates rising from 16-24 percent to 18-24
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspapers reported Wednesday that commercial
bank's average base lending rate rose to 20.26 percent last week
from 19.94 percent in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The country's top five banks, Barclays, Standard Chartered,
National Bank, Cooperative Bank and its subsidiary Co-op
Merchant, and the Kenya Commercial Bank group, are at the bottom
rank of 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
While Mashreq Bank is the highest in base rate at 24 percent
and the majority of the 47 banks listed are in the 18.3 to 23.5
percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Liquidity in the domestic financial market eased last week,
with the interbank overnight rates falling to 12.33 percent from
13.54 percent in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign exchange market, the paper noted, the shilling
weakened against the dollar last week to 74.20 shillings from
74.13 shillings in the previous week, but the local currency
strengthened against the euro and the British pound.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government Monday issued special bonds worth 13.76
million U. S. dollars, the second series of issues to raise cash
to repay contractors and suppliers owed money by the government.
</P>
<P>
In June, the government issued the first series of special
bonds worth 940 million shillings (11.95 million dollars) and a
third series of special bonds estimated at 13.76 million dollars
will be issued in September, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
