<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Negotiators Make Progress on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators have made progress on the issue of Palestinian
prisoners in their latest talks, agreeing to draw up a list of 650
prisoners for review, Israel Radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's envoy Gilad Sher and senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat met for more than five hours
in Jerusalem Tuesday evening after they failed to resolve
difference on a timetable for the implementation of the Wye
agreement in their previous negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In their latest talks, the negotiators set aside the major
issue of timetable and focused on issues including the safe
passages between the West Bank and Gaza and the release of
Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
"The talks were substantial, positive and warm, with progress
being made on all issues on the agenda," Barak's office said in a
statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A joint Israeli-Palestinian committee on the matter of
prisoners, which met Tuesday for the first time, would meet again
to examine the list of prisoners, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said after the late-night talks that he expected Israel
to release the political prisoners, or those were jailed for
anti-Israel activities, before implementation of the Wye accord
begins on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye accord, Israel is to release 750 Palestinian
political prisoners in three stages. Barak's predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu ordered the release of 250 prisoners last November, but
most of the released were common criminals instead of political
prisoners the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) had required.
</P>
<P>
The dispute sparked weeks of bloodiest violence in years
between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in the West Bank and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
There have been signs that the new moderate government of
Barak would ease the criteria for the release of prisoners to
include more political ones on the list.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami from the Labor Party
said Tuesday that there is logic in Palestinians' demand that all
political prisoners be released under the framework of a permanent
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israel's security cabinet will hold a special meeting later on
Wednesday to discuss the release issue, Israeli media said.
</P>
<P>
The government is looking into the possibility that
accessories to terrorist actions ending in bloodshed shall not be
considered terrorists "with blood on their hands," the media
reported.
</P>
<P>
Since taking office on July 6, Barak has promised to carry out
the Wye agreement, but he has been at odds with PNA Chairman
Yasser Arafat over when the implementation would be completed.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Israel has to hand over another 11 percent of
the West Bank to the Palestinians in the last two
stages. Netanyahu suspended the agreement in early December after
turning over 2 percent in first stage.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have reached agreement on Barak's proposal to
restart the accord on September 1 and carry out the second stage
of troop withdrawal on October 1.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians have repeatedly rejected Barak's
suggestion to postpone the final stage of redeployment until
February 2000, when the final-status talks dealing with thorny
issues like Jerusalem and settlements are supposed to have been
well under way.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have said that the final stage should be
completed by mid-November in line with the original timetable of
the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Haaretz reported Wednesday that Israel is now
taking a more flexible stance and proposing to complete the final
redeployment by January 15, one month before the date originally
proposed by Barak.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted diplomatic sources as saying that the
Palestinians are prepared to accept a completion of the
redeployment by the end of December or the beginning of January.
</P>
<P>
If the Palestinians agree to the new timeline proposed by the
Israeli side, Israel is prepared to begin implementing the second
stage of troop withdrawal before October 1, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
