<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Summit Opens in Mozambican Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The 19th Summit of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) opened here Wednesday morning
with its theme of "SADC in the Next Millennium: Working Together
for Peace, Progress and Prosperity."
</P>
<P>
After a short opening ceremony at the City Hall in Mozambican
capital Maputo, the leaders or representatives of the 14 member
states closed themselves up.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss issues on the conflicts in Angola, and the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the relations between
Angola and Zambia and the elections in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a military intervention in Angola has almost
been ruled out as Angola insists that the SADC should do what it
was created for.
</P>
<P>
However, Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos said at the
celebration meeting in Maputo on the SADC Day Tuesday that his
government will not negotiate with the UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Dos Santos said that the National Union for Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) led by Jonas Savimbi has violated the
U.N.-brokered 1994 Lusaka Peace Accord by renewing the civil war.
</P>
<P>
And the Angolan president demanded that the Lusaka peace accord
should still be the base of any new peace initiative for Angola.
</P>
<P>
Host Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano also said that "we
must condemn all forces of the region that use violence and crime
as means to conquer power."
</P>
<P>
Zambian president Frederic Chilluba is expected to deliver a
report on the DRC peace process as required by the last summit in
Mauritius last September.
</P>
<P>
Chilluba did not appear at the celebration meeting Tuesday and
Chissano said that the Zambian president was busy on his DRC
report.
</P>
<P>
On the economic scene, the regional leaders will review the
performance of member states in the past year and the negative
effect on economy in individual country and the region as a whole
of the continuing armed conflicts in some SADC countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will focus on the food security situation in the
region which needs some 2.88 million tons of cereals for the
1999/2000 marketing year.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the leaders may again voice their
call for more debt relief for the poor countries, especially those
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The service of external debt in African countries including the
majority of the SADC members reaches some 30 percent of their
total public revenues, diverting much money from the basic needs
in such areas as health, education, water and others.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has just achieved the relief of a part of its
external debt under the Heavily-Indebted Poor Countries
initiative.
</P>
<P>
But Chissano, who is also the Vice Chairman of the SADC, said
that the weight of debt is still hight if the socio-economic
reality of his country is taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that "the partial cancellation is not the
solution."
</P>
<P>
The leaders are also expected to sign on two protocols, one on
wildlife conservation and law enforcement, and the other on
health, as well as a declaration of productivity.
</P>
<P>
The sale of gold by Britain and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will be addressed too at the Maputo summit.
</P>
<P>
Due to urgent calls back home, DRC President Laurent Kabila did
not attend the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who arrived in Maputo Monday and was supposed to make a
 statement at the SADC Day celebration, went back to Kinshasa
Tuesday to deal with urgent domestic affairs. Founding fathers
of the regional organizations such as Nelson Mandela, Kenneth
Kaunda also attended the opening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
