<HEADLINE> Charter-change Hoopla Blamed for Philippine Stock Market Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Edgardo Espiritu blamed Wednesday the sudden slump of the stock
market on the continuous charter-change hoopla which eventually
led to a rift between the government and the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said many observers think changes in the 1987
Constitution are urgently needed particularly on the economic
aspects considering that some of them are no longer attuned to the
present conditions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The finance chief noted that because many opponents of the
charter-change threat to sow chaos during their nationwide rallies
on Friday, many foreign fund investors have pulled out their
investments in the equities market.
</P>
<P>
At the Philippine Stock Exchange, the 33-share composite index
tumbled as much as 4.05 percent to 2,087.13 points on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu believed, however, that these foreign fund managers
who decided to withdraw their investments and shifted them
elsewhere will return when apprehensions spawned by the rallies on
charter-change are over.
</P>
<P>
Notably, foreign fund investors are sensitive to economic
jitters so that they do not want to gamble in a situation that
will put their investments in a negative situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Espiritu, this is something which the government
cannot prevent because there is no law that is applicable to this
effect.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed confidence that the influx of foreign fund
investments into the country will normalize after the mist of
doubts on the charter-change rallies is ironed out next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
