<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Israeli Soldiers Killed in Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel confirmed Wednesday
that two of its soldiers were killed and seven others wounded
Tuesday in clashes with Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The clashes are the fiercest that occurred in south Lebanon
since Israel launched a large-scale air raids on Lebanon in June,
avenging the killing of Israeli civilians in northern Israel, in
which 10 Lebanese were killed, Israeli media reported.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, St.-Sgt. Eyal Gueta, 21, was killed in a clash
between a squad of Israeli soldiers and Hezbollah guerrillas in
the thick bush of Wadi Salouki in the Israeli-occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
The two sides encountered again when the Israeli army tried to
evacuate the casualties, in which Sgt. Doron Hershkowitz, 20, was
killed.
</P>
<P>
Seven others, including a battalion commander, were wounded in
the two fightings, with three of them in serious condition. The
army said three Hezbollah guerrillas were killed in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The deaths brought to 12 the number of Israeli soldiers killed
in southern Lebanon this year.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a war of attrition to
oust Israeli troops and their allied South Lebanon Army from a
15-kilometer deep occupation zone in south Lebanon Israel carved
out in 1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes struck back, repeatedly raiding suspected
Hezbollah positions inside the zone. Fierce artillery, mortar and
rocket firings raged for nearly four hours after the killings.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah announced that the gunfight was in retaliation for
the death of Ali Deeb, a regional Hezbollah field commander, who
was killed Monday by two roadside bombs outside the port city of
Sidon in Lebanon. Hezbollah blamed Israel for the death.
</P>
<P>
But Chief of Israel's Northern Command Gabi Ashkenazi denied
there was any connection between the clashes and the death of
Deeb, who was on the top of Israel's most wanted list for
carrying out attacks against the Israeli army in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz Tuesday also denied
Hezbollah's charges that Israel was behind the death of Deeb,
suggesting that the killing might have been the result of an
internal struggle among guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
The latest Israeli casualties will undoubtedly enhance a
domestic cry for a quick Israeli withdrawal from the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Assuming office in early July, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak has promised to pull Israeli troops out of southern Lebanon
within a year through negotiations with Syria, Beirut's main
power-broker.
</P>
<P>
Before the news of the fatalities was released to the public,
Barak said Tuesday that Israel would continue to do everything
possible to pull the Israeli army back to the international border
so that there would be quiet in the area.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria are apparently awaiting a visit to the region
by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright scheduled in early
September which is aimed at restarting the Israeli-Syrian talks
broke off three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The main issue in the talks will be the fate of the Golan
Heights, a Syrian strategic plateau seized by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
