<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches Health Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
launched a five- year national health sector and AIDS control
strategic plan with an objective to increase the longevity and
equality of Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Jackson Kalweo said here Tuesday that the
1999-2004 plan aims at reducing the prevalence of HIV/AIDS and
increase the level and quality of care for those already
infected, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan was estimated to cost 84 billion shillings
(1.2 billion U.S. dollars), out of which 2.3 billion shillings
(32 million U.S. dollars) would go towards the HIV/ AIDS control
program.
</P>
<P>
Kalweo noted that with the expected resources, a financing gap
of 24 percent is anticipated, saying this will be financed
through additional resources from the Treasury, development
partners, private sector and the non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The plan covers six priority areas: malaria prevention and
treatment; reproductive health; HIV/AIDS and tuberculosis
prevention and management; integrated management of childhood
illness and immunization; prevention and control of major
environmental health-related diseases; and food safety.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the plan would ensure equitable allocation
of government resources to reduce disparities in health, continue
to manage the population growth and create an environment for
private sector and community involvement in health service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
