<HEADLINE> Egyptians Fly to Sudan to Mediate Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has sent a delegation to
Sudan to help mediate between the government and opposition groups
to end the country's 16-year-old civil war, a national newspaper
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Arabic Al-Ahram daily said the Egyptian delegation flew
out of Cairo airport alongside a Libyan delegation to the Sudanese
capital of Khartoum Tuesday night in a joint effort to open
national reconciliation conference between the Sudanese government
and the opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government paper quoted airport officials as saying
that the Egyptian delegation was headed by Assistant Foreign
Minister for the Sudanese Affairs Fouad Youssef. The Libyan
delegation was only described as "high-level."
</P>
<P>
The mission followed a five-day strategy meeting of Sudanese
opposition leaders in the Libyan capital of Tripoli that ended on
August 1. At the meeting, the Sudanese National Democratic
Alliance (NDA) agreed to accept Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi's
offer to mediate in Sudan's civil war.
</P>
<P>
The NDA groups northern Sudanese parties that are seeking
democracy and the Sudan People's Liberation Army, which seeks
autonomy for the Christian and animist people of the south.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has also been mediating between the two rival sides, with
Sudanese officials and opposition leaders coming regularly to
Cairo to meet Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's war and related famine have claimed more than 1.9
million lives since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
