<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Ask Uganda for Reinforcements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, leader
of Uganda- backed rebel group based in Kisangani in the northeast
of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), has asked Uganda to
send in reinforcements in defense of the Congolese population.
</P>
<P>
Wamba made the appeal Tuesday after he was driven out of a
hotel in the city center, the New Vision newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Two battalions of his rebel force and Ugandan troops are
fighting four brigades of Rwandan troops, the rebel leader was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The elderly scholar-turned politician, who was ousted from the
leadership of the main rebel group, the Congolese Rally for
Democracy (RCD), in mid-May, fled his headquarters in Hotel
Wagenia in Kisangani and was hiding in an undisclosed location in
the city, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Half of his executive could have died in the hotel as half the
hotel was destroyed at dawn by Rwandan troops, according to the
rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
The division among RCD leadership led to the rebel group's
splitting into RCD-Goma backed by Rwanda and RCD-Kisangani
supported by Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that Uganda is helping training new recruits
for Wamba as the military muscle of the RCD was mainly controlled
by RCD-Goma.
</P>
<P>
Kampala, however, has denied supporting any of the factions of
the split rebel group. 
</P>
