<HEADLINE> China to Develop Movie on American Voluntary Aerocade in World War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- American social activist Anna
Chan Chennault has reached an agreement with China to develop a
feature movie about her husband general Chennault in World War II.
</P>
<P>
The title of the movie is named after Chennault, who was the
commander of the US 14th Air Fleet during the second World War.
Anna Chen will interpret the homonymic role in the movie.
</P>
<P>
Claire Lee Chennault had organized American voluntary pilots
into an aerocade known as the Flying Tiger Fleet during the Second
World War. He and his men transported arms and other materials,
and joined in the air raid, supporting China against Japanese
invaders.
</P>
<P>
Many of the pilots were killed during the war and people are
still searching for their remains in China's mountainous regions.
</P>
<P>
The movie will reproduce the history and tell stories of the
members of the Flying Tiger Fleet and their offsprings, as well as
the love between Anna and her husband.
</P>
<P>
A Hollywood actor will play the leading role of the general.
</P>
<P>
The Overseas Chinese Artists Association of United States
assessed that the theme of the movie reflects a trans-national
humanistic significance.
</P>
<P>
The experience of the couple, a warrior in the past and an
envoy of peace at present, would bring people a far-reaching self-
reflection of the war launched by human in the 20th century, and
lead people to pray for the peace of the 21st century, the
association was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The director of the film is Qin Jian, who is famous for his
film "Huangpu Love". He has been invited to visit Western Europe
and the United States. In 1994, he developed a documentary for the
then European Community, which was the first practice for a
Chinese director.
</P>
<P>
Qin also directed the first film describing the warfield of
China, India and Burma in the Second World War. In 1998, another
film of his "the Chinese Crusaders" had been issued abroad in
several languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
