<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polluting Enterprises in S.W. China Asked to Make Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan Province in southwest
China has issued a circular calling on government departments at
all levels to guarantee that all 1,042 key polluting enterprises
meet the required discharge standards set by the state before the
end of the century.
</P>
<P>
This constitutes part of Yunnan's effort to implement the
central government's policy concerning ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
The circular reiterates that those enterprises which fail to
meet with the set standards before the deadline have to be closed.
</P>
<P>
It has been learned that 244 of such polluting enterprises have
met with the waste discharge standard and passed inspection after
a year's effort and 10 enterprises have shut down and 195
enterprises are undergoing improvement.
</P>
<P>
Situated in southwestern China, Yunnan has relatively less-
developed industry. However, half of the lakes on the Yunnan-
Guizhou plateau, including the famous Dianchi Lake, the sixth
largest freshwater lake in the country, were seriously polluted.
</P>
<P>
The 1,042 enterprises, which cover petrochemical, metallurgical,
power and building material sectors, include the industrial
enterprises that consume 15,000 tons of coal annually or release
100 tons of waste liquids daily. Those industrial enterprises,
which have caused serious environment pollution in urban areas,
are also included. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Population Reaches 19 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Australia's population has
reached 19 million but the nation's annual growth rate remains
among the lowest in the world, the Australian Bureau of Statistics
(ABS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figures of the ABS indicate it will take another six years
before the population hits 20 million.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the population milestone in Sydney, Minister for
Financial Services and Regulation Joe Hockey said "today,
Australia has just passed a population of 19 million."
</P>
<P>
"The 19-millionth person is likely to be a little girl born in
an Australian hospital."
</P>
<P>
He added that it had taken four years and five months for the
population to increase from 18 million to 19 million.
</P>
<P>
During that time, natural increase had accounted for 53 percent
of the growth and migration had contributed 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
The population increased by a net 558 a day - 681 babies were
born, 369 people died and 246 immigrants were added.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated Australia's population would reach 20 million
by 2005 and increase to 26 million in 2050, Hockey said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ABS demography director John Paice said the world's
population was increasing by about 80 million a year, or 1.3
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
