<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More New Zealand Women Have Late Childbearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The trend away from early
childbearing is continuing in New Zealand with the number of women
having a child in their teens or early 20s declining, according to
an official press release out here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the release, New Zealand's Deputy Government Statistician
Dianne Macaskill said the 30-34 year age group is now the second
commonest age group for childbearing.
</P>
<P>
"In the year to June 1999, 112 out of every 1,000 New Zealand
women aged 30-34 years gave birth, well up from 105 per 1,000 in
1991. The estimated average age of New Zealand women giving birth
is now 29.1 years, compared with 28.9 years in 1998 and 27.8 years
 in 1991," Macaskill said.
</P>
<P>
The estimated number of live births in the year totaled 56,843,
while deaths registered totaled 27,202 in New Zealand with a
population of 3.8 million.
</P>
<P>
Birth rates for the year suggest that New Zealand women average
1.97 births per woman, which is marginally below the level of 2.1
births per woman required for the population to replace itself
without migration, the deputy government statistician said.
</P>
</TEXT>
