<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Oil Import Up To 9.8 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- With oil prices on the rise in
the international market, India is expected to pay 9.8 billion
U.S. dollars for its oil import bill during the current financial
year which ends in March 2000.
</P>
<P>
The import bill should be at least 30 percent higher than last
year's 7.5 billion U.S. dollars, 0.5 billion U.S. dollars more
than the all-time high of 9.32 billion dollars in 1996-97, the
Indian Express reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The country imported 57 million tons of crude oil and petroleum
products last year and paid 7.39 billion U.S. dollars for 53
million tons of oil a year before.
</P>
<P>
The fast soaring crude oil price coincides with a nearly 40
percent increase in its oil refining capacity, which has gone up
to 67 million tons with 15 refineries in the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that India's import bill could go up
further if crude oil and petroleum products continue to get dearer
at the present rate.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices have doubled since January, when the
prevailing rates were roughly 9 U.S. dollars a barrel, while
petroleum product prices have increased by more than 30 percent
since March, when crude prices turned the corner at 11 U.S.
dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
India has planned to increase its crude imports to nearly 60
million tons by the end of next March from roughly 38 million tons
last year while petroleum product imports would drop drastically
to half of last year's level with the increase in the indigenous
availability of diesel, kerosene and liquefied petroleum gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
