<HEADLINE> Seismologists: No Connection Between Quakes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Seismologists here Wednesday
said there is no connection between Tuesday's disastrous
earthquake in Turkey and the quake that rocked Cyprus last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A strong aftershock measuring 4.8 degrees on the Richter scale
was felt in Cyprus Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday's quake, measuring 5.8 degrees, caused dozens of
injuries and damaged many buildings, especially in Cyprus'
southern coastal Limassol area where the epicenter was located.
</P>
<P>
The quake was followed by dozens of aftershocks, many of them
strong enough to be felt in Limassol and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
But local seismologists believe that seismic activity in the
Cyprus area is coming to the end of a ten-year active cycle and
would peter out in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
"These aftershocks were now waning," said Sotiris Aphrodisis,
the acting head of Cyprus' Geological Survey Department.
</P>
<P>
In February 1995, two people were killed when an earthquake
with a magnitude of 5.7 degrees jolted Cyprus' western Paphos
area. In October 1996, a 6.3-degree quake caused minor damages but
no fatalities on the island.
</P>
<P>
The news of the huge quake in Turkey, which has so far killed
more than 2,500 people and injured tens of thousands, raised fears
that a similar catastrophe might be round the corner for Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
