<HEADLINE> Egyptian Journalist Freed After Agreeing to Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- An opposition Egyptian journalist
has been released after agreeing to pay a fine of 20,000 Egyptian
pounds (5,900 U.S. dollars) imposed by a court for libeling
Egypt's deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Wednesday that Adel
Hussein, a columnist for the Islamist Al-Shaab newspaper, the
fiery mouthpiece of the opposition Labor Party, was set free on
Monday after he agreed to pay the fine in instalments, a
compromise reached with the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, who is also deputy chairman of the Labor Party, was
arrested Monday and detained for eight hours for refusing to pay
the fine immediately in protest against the court sentence, the
English-language newspaper quoted security sources as saying on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The South Cairo Criminal Court on Saturday convicted Hussein
and three other Al-Shaab journalists of libeling Deputy Prime
Minister Youssef Wali in a series of articles and cartoons that
accused him of "treason" and "working as an agent for" Israel and
trying to ruin Egypt's economy.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the same amount of fines, the other three
journalists were sentenced to two years in prison with hard labor,
the maximum allowed under a 1996 press law.
</P>
<P>
Wali, who is also the minister of agriculture, has signed a
number of agreements with Israel for the supply of seed,
fertilizers and technology to arrest desertification.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shaab is published by the Labor Party, which is allied to
the Muslim Brotherhood - Egypt's strongest Islamic movement - and
opposes peace with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
