<HEADLINE> Nathan Declared Singapore's President-Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's
ambassador-at-large S.R. Nathan Wednesday was declared the
country's second elected president.
</P>
<P>
As the sole candidate declared by the Presidential Elections
Committee (PEC) eligible for the elections, Nathan met with no
rivals and thus became the president-elect automatically.
</P>
<P>
Nathan, the island country's sixth president and the second
elected president, will begin his term on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Ong Teng Cheong is the first elected president after Singapore
adopted the new presidential system in 1993. His term will end on
August 31.
</P>
<P>
In his first speech after being declared the president elect,
Nathan said he was "humbled and very moved" by this honor to be
the new president.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed appreciation to all who have supported him in
his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Nathan presented his nomination papers
after nominations for the presidential election opened on the
morning of Wednesday, the Nomination Day.
</P>
<P>
Nathan, a veteran civil servant and Chairman of the Institute
of Defense and Strategic Studies, received a Certificate of
Eligibility (COE) from the PEC on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The other two unsuccessful applicants, private tutor Ooi Boon
Ewe and insurance agent Tan Soon Phuan, were rejected by the PEC
on reasons that they did not meet all the requirements for the
issue of COE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
