<HEADLINE> Bayi Refuses to Release Wang Zhizhi to NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bayi Rockets of the Chinese
Basketball Association has dicided not to release its center Wang
Zhizhi to play in the NBA league for the Dallas Mavericks, said a
top official of the Chinese army club on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It's a nice thing that Wang was selected by Dallas at the NBA
draft on June 30," Qian Limin, manager of the Bayi club, told
Xinhua in a telephone interview. "But we cann't let him go because
it's not a right time either for our team or for Wang himself.
</P>
<P>
"Wang, who stands 2.12 meters, is our only top center. We cann'
t afford losing him now.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, it's too early for Wang to play in the NBA as far
as his age and weak physical ability is concerned."
</P>
<P>
The Bayi Rockets won its fifth consecutive CBA league title
last season with Wang playing a crucial role.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Basketball Association has said it will respect the
decision of the club.
</P>
<P>
Ross Perot, owner of the Dallas Mavericks, team's coach Don
Nelson and his assistant Donn Nelson, have arrived in Beijing and
will talk with the Bayi Rockets and the CBA.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is the first Asian player to be selected in the NBA
draft, will leave for Japan to play the Asian Baskestball
Championship for his country. 
</P>
