<HEADLINE> IMF to Study ASEAN Currency Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has requested the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to carry out a study on the
strengths, weaknesses, pre-conditions and implications of adopting
an ASEAN currency.
</P>
<P>
The study by the IMF requested by Bank Negara Malaysia (State
Bank of Malaysia) is expected to be completed in October and the
result will be used as a concept working paper on the adoption of
an ASEAN currency, Malaysia's National Economic Action Council
(NEAC) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia suggested a study on the feasibility and prerequisites
of adopting an ASEAN currency at a future date and this will have
to be examined within the context of intra-ASEAN trade as well as
trade between ASEAN and other trading partners, the NEAC said in
its 17th Progress Report on the status of implementation of the
National Economic Recovery Plan.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
