<HEADLINE> China's National Ethnic Games Opens at Tibet Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- With the Ode to Good Luck
reverberating over the venue, the sixth national ethnic games
opens here on Wednesday, adding another note of jubilation to the
Tibet Autonomous Region (TAG) which was celebrating its 40th
anniversary of the Democratic Reform.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the TAG stage such sports gala
which draws 33 delegations from all over the country, and features
four competitive events and 43 for exhibition.
</P>
<P>
A total of 25 golds are at stake as athletes from 31 ethnic
minorities will take part in such competitive events like horse
racing, top whipping, yajia (similar to tug-of-war) and shenu (
similar to arrow shooting).
</P>
<P>
The sixth national ethnic games is split between Lhasa and
Beijing, the main venue which will stage the other nine
competitive events next month.
</P>
<P>
The TAG have witnessed substantial changes since 1959 when the
democratic reform began, abolishing the feudal system and
separating religion from government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
