<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Lobbies Thailand on WTO Farm Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Agriculture Minister
Shoichi Nakagawa has lobbied Thailand to take a sympathetic stance
with Japan on agricultural issues at the upcoming round of World
Trade Organization (WTO) talks.
</P>
<P>
The Nation, a leading English newspaper here, reported
Wednesday that Nakagawa discussed the issue in Bangkok with Thai
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi who will succeed Mike
Moore of New Zealand as the director-general of the WTO in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the Japanese government has urged Thailand to
take into consideration that agricultural trade should not be
considered purely as a commercial activity. Other aspects
including food security and the balance of supply and demand in
farm exporting countries should also be considered, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
WTO members are set to meet in Seattle, the United States, in
December this year to prepare for the next round of trade
negotiations. The U.S. officials had earlier said that the U.S.
administration would place a high priority on opening up the world
farm trade.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government, strongly pressured by domestic
farmers, has, however, been trying to protect them by limiting
access to the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
In a written proposal on the upcoming WTO negotiation which
will be presented to Thai officials, the Japanese government said
that members should allow for a smooth implementation of domestic
agriculture policies and the differences in national conditions.
</P>
<P>
Regarding food security, Japan said consideration should be
given to this aspect of agriculture by taking into account the
instability of food supply and demand in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the members should also redress the imbalances in
rights and obligations under the WTO rules between exporting and
importing countries.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this, the members should strengthen the existing
rules and disciplines on export restrictions with a view to
redressing rights and obligations between exporting and importing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
