<HEADLINE> Cambodia Bans "Two China" Activities in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen signed a government decree Wednesday banning government and
military officials at all levels from taking part in any
activities held by Taiwan separatists in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The decree was aimed at the recent reports that some Taiwanese
elements attempt to mark Taiwan's so-called "National Day" on
October 10 in Cambodia and illegally use Taiwan's "flag" and
"anthem".
</P>
<P>
The government announcement pointed out that the aim of the
activity is to pursue a "two China" policy and to reopen the
Taiwan office in Cambodia which was forced to close in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the above-mentioned facts, the Royal Government of
Cambodia reiterates that Cambodia always pursues 'one China'
policy and recognizes Taiwan as an integral part of the People's
Republic of China," the decree said.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan issue is the internal affair of China. Any attempt to
admit Taiwan as an independent country is not only a brutal
violation of the sovereignty of the People's Republic of China,
but also a blasphemy against King Norodom Sihanouk as well as a
violation of the principle of the Kingdom of Cambodia," it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The decree urged various government departments and the
officials in various cities and provinces to take every measure to
ban such illegal activity held by Taiwanese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
