<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues New Accountant Rules for Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Finance
issues a new set of rules on accountancy of non-monetary
transactions for enterprises this week.
</P>
<P>
The new rules, which will take effect from January 1 of next
year, are designed to regulate the accounting of and release of
information about non-monetary transactions of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A finance ministry official in charge of accountant rules said
this is the first set of accountant rules that the ministry
promulgated this year.
</P>
<P>
The new rules are adopted to cope with changes in enterprise
management and the development of securities market, he noted,
adding that the application of the rules will, to some extent,
prevent enterprises from using non-monetary transactions as means
to manipulate profits.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he added, the new rules filled into a blank in China
's accountant regulations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok New Airport to Handle Int'l Flights in 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok's new international
airport will handle all international passenger flights when it
starts operation in 2004, the Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahidol Chantrangkun, permanent secretary of the Transport and
Communications Ministry, was quoted by the newspaper as saying
that the new airport, named Nong Ngu Hao, will handle all
passenger flights originating in Bangkok in the long run.
</P>
<P>
He said that upon inauguration, the Nong Ngu Hao airport will
be able to handle 30 million passengers annually.
</P>
<P>
The present Bangkok International Airport at Don Muang will
then handle all domestic flights with an estimated 7 million
passengers annually.
</P>
<P>
In 2006, the Transport and Communications Ministry plans to
expand the Nong Ngu Hao airport to serve all domestic and
international flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
