<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador, Colombia Urged to Settle Trade Dispute in WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- An official of the Andean Nations
Community (CAN) proposed Tuesday that Ecuador and Colombia look
for a solution to their trade dispute from the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Colombia imposed tighter import controls on Ecuadorian fruit
products last week, banning the entrance of several varieties on
sanitary ground. The affected products include banana, lemon,
avocado, mango, pineapple, dry coconut, raspberry, papaya and
strawberry.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Ecuadorian Service of Agricultural Sanitation,
Emilio Raymond, said that his country has exhausted all means in
seeking an end to the trade dispute.
</P>
<P>
Michael Badolla, responsible for the CAN's Andean Agricultural
Sanitation Project, said that although Ecuador and Colombia are
both CAN members, they do not follow the bloc's rules. Therefore
the most obvious path to find a solution is to go to the WTO, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The CAN is made up of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, Ecuadorian fruit exports
to Colombia reached almost 1.7 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
