<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Expects 4 Million Tourists by Year 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Ministry of
Tourism is seeking to promote regional tourism to meet its target
of 4 million tourist arrivals by the year 2004, press reports said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
To improve tourism figures, Sri Lanka is preparing to meet the
needs of the diverse range of visitors by responding to market
trends and meet the requirements of discerning and sophisticated
visitors, the Island reported.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis will be given to regional tourism, the delivery of the
best practice service standards and enhancing the industry's
information base.
</P>
<P>
Many of Sri Lanka's prominent tourist attractions are found in
regional areas and many niche markets such as ecotourism, rural
tourism, indigenous tourism, backpacking and adventure tourism
have their focus in regional Sri Lanka, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, Sri Lanka will seek to encourage tourists to
travel beyond the boundaries of traditional metropolitan gateways
to regional areas.
</P>
<P>
The government will also direct its attention at enhancing
community awareness and involvement in the industry to ensure the
sustainable development of the tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, tourists arrivals to Sri Lanka rose by 4.1 percent to
381,063 over the previous year. Earnings last year reached 200
million U.S. dollars, making tourism the third largest foreign
exchange source for the country.
</P>
<P>
The Tourist Board has predicted a 17 percent rise in tourist
arrivals this year to 446,000. Tourist arrivals for the first half
of 1999 rose to 212,766, up nearly 23 percent over the same period
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
