<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 2,000 Killed, Over 10,000 Injured in Turkish Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,000 people were
killed and over 10,000 others injured in a powerful earthquake
that rocked western Turkey early Tuesday, the Anatolia news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Citing a statement issued by the government crisis center in
the capital city, the report said that the overall death toll by
late Tuesday reached 2,011 and the number of the injured stood at
10,764.
</P>
<P>
In Izmit, where the quake was centered, 844 people were killed
and 2,897 wounded, the center said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, measuring 6.8 on the open-ended Richter scale,
struck the western and central Anatolian provinces, the country's
most populous region, at 3:02 a.m. local time (0002 GMT) Tuesday
and lasted about 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people in the cities of Istanbul, Izmit and Ankara
spent the night out in the open air or in their cars for fear of
aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
Using picks, shovels and other tools, rescuers and local
residents frantically searched for survivors buried under the
debris. Hundreds of persons were still missing, rescue officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The quake claimed 560 lives and injured 2,600 people in Sakarya,
the neighboring province to Izmit, while in Yalova town, on the
Marmara Sea coast, the death toll stood at 229 and the number of
the injured was given as 1,431.
</P>
<P>
In Istanbul, Turkey's biggest city with a population of 10
million, a total of 215 people were killed and 3,250 wounded, the
center said.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul, Izmit, Sakarya, Bursa, Bolu, Yalova and Eskisehir
have been declared as "disaster areas" by the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the international community has begun to send aid to
the country. The Anatolia news agency said 70 Russian surgeons, 60
Azeri rescue specialists and a German Red Cross team have arrived
in the country to help with the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and Iranian President Mohammad Khatami sent condolences
and pledged aid to the country.
</P>
<P>
Other countries, including Sweden, Hungary, Austria, the Czech
Republic, also offered assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
