<HEADLINE> Poland, Germany, Denmark Stage Computer-Simulated Maneuver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Poland, Germany and Denmark on
Tuesday started a computer-simulated maneuver code-named "Baltic
Cooperation" in Szczecin of northwestern Poland.
</P>
<P>
It is the first military maneuver Poland has joined within the
framework of peaceful partnership since it joined NATO in March,
said the Polish Press Agency (PAP).
</P>
<P>
About 300 officers from NATO's Northeastern International
Division, consisting of three divisions (one from each of the
navies of the three countries), participated in the maneuver. The
command of the Division, General Henrik Ekmann from Denmark, was
monitoring the whole maneuver, which was entirely held on computer
screens, plastic maps and charts.
</P>
<P>
Lithuanian and Latvian officers were invited to participate in
the maneuver as guests.
</P>
<P>
The maneuver will end on August 26. 
</P>
