<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts Executes Long-Delayed Verdicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's Court (
SPC) said Tuesday that local courts had executed forcible
enforcement of rulings on five cases that had been long delayed,
local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The move shows the SPC's strong its determination to tackle the
widespread practices of interference and resistance to enforcement
of court rulings, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Such interference and resistance were rooted in local and
departmental protectionism, according to Li Guoguang, vice-
president of the SPC.
</P>
<P>
All the courts in the country will make full use of all the
compulsory measures permitted by the law to carry out court
rulings, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed that those who illegally meddle in the execution of
the cases will be held legally responsible, thus ensuring that
court rulings are effectively administered.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that up to the end of June, more than 850,
000 court rulings, involving 259 billion yuan (about 31.2 billion
U.S. dollars), were yet to be executed.
</P>
<P>
The five cases of forcible enforcement took place in Guangdong,
Henan, Jilin and Jiangxi provinces and Beijing, in which four
people were under judicial detention or arrest now.
</P>
<P>
An intensive campaign against the difficulties in executing
court rulings, a plague that has long worried the Chinese courts,
was carried out in the last four months of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
