<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Economy to Shrink 7 Percent This Year, Says Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's economy will shrink 7
percent this year, the country's central bank forecast on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The transport and communication sector is expected to register
the biggest fall of 9.3 percent, followed by 9.2 percent in the
manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank expects a 2.7 percent gain in agriculture
and fishing, the only area to register an increase.
</P>
<P>
The South American country, laden with an 18.1 percent
unemployment figure, a 62.5 percent poverty rate, and more than 16
billion U.S. dollars in foreign debt, is facing its worst economic
crisis in the decade.
</P>
<P>
President Jamil Mahuad's government, expecting an agreement
with the International Monetary Fund, foresees a 2 percent
economic surge in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
