<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Economy Grows Solidly in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's economy grew
steadily in the first half of this year with its Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) up 2.5 percent over the same period in 1998, said a
report from the finance secretary's office on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the GDP jumped by 3.2 percent from April to
June due to the "dynamism of the industrial sector," which grew by
4.4 percent, followed by the service and agricultural sectors,
which advanced by 2.9 and 2.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Within the industrial sector, the construction activity
rocketed by 5.7 percent, followed by the manufacturing and
electrical generating, gas and water sectors with 4.9 percent
together.
</P>
<P>
Mining production registered a steep fall of 6.4 percent, said
the official report.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, the only major economy in Latin America to post solid
growth this year, has set the goal for the whole year at a 3.0
percent growth of its GDP, 13 percent in inflation and 1.25
percent in public deficit.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict the 2.5 percent growth in GDP in the first
half of the year would put the economy on track to meet or even
exceed the government target for the year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Mexican exports increased 10 percent to 64
billion U.S. dollars during the mentioned period, despite a strong
peso, the country's currency, which made goods less competitive in
price.
</P>
<P>
Some economists attribute the hike to a robust U.S. economy,
because about 80 percent of Mexican exports go to its northern
neighbor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
