<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Aid Offered After Turkey's Quake Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The international community
extended condolences and pledged aid on Tuesday to Turkey in the
aftermath of a devastating earthquake that hit the country in the
middle of the night, killing more than 2,000 people and injuring
thousands.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government has decided to provide three to four
million krona (about 370,000 to 490,000 U.S. dollars) in emergency
aid for the relief effort, the Swedish foreign ministry said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be mainly used to fund a rescue group composed
of 30 experts and 12 sniffer dogs to help search and rescue people
still buried in the ruins.
</P>
<P>
A six-member special rescue team left Hungary on Tuesday
afternoon for the quake-stricken areas in Turkey. The team, made
up of medical and technical workers, brought along two sniffer
dogs in addition to specialized equipment to locate those trapped
in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
Austria said it would send 60 special technical troops to the
disaster areas on Tuesday night to assist the search and rescue
efforts in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic promised to send heavy digging machinery and
specially trained dogs to help look for survivors. Other aid
programs are being under emergency negotiations, a Czech foreign
ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian government has committed to send as early as
Tuesday night a team of rescuers and sniffer dogs provided by the
Bulgarian Red Cross to the quake-hit areas in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The quake, measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale, struck Izmit, a
northwestern industrial city about 90 kilometers east of Turkey's
largest city, Istanbul, at 3:02 a.m. local time (0020 GMT). Most
of the dead were crushed in their sleep.
</P>
<P>
As many as 10,000 people are feared still trapped in the rubble
around Golcuk, a navy base town about 130 kilometers southeast of
Istanbul. Thousands more were missing in Istanbul and elsewhere.
The power supply has been cut off in the disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
The overall death toll by late Tuesday, according to the semi-
official Anatolia news agency, was at 2,011 and the injuries
totaled 10,764.
</P>
<P>
Israel, Germany, Japan and Greece have also pledged to provide
aid to the quake-devastated Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
