<HEADLINE> Mexico's Tourism Revenue Surpasses Petroleum Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Mexico received 20 million
overseas visitors and its tourism revenue reached 8 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998, surpassing that of petroleum exports for the
first time, Mexico's Secretary of Tourism Oscar Espinosa said on
Tuesday in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Espinosa also revealed
Mexico's tourism industry now represents 8.2 percent of its GDP
and creates 1.7 million jobs.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is the seventh most attractive tourism destination and
the 13th in tourism revenue of the world, Espinosa added.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is fundamental for the development of Latin American
countries, he said, because it can efficiently abate the economic
and social problems brought by the fast growing population.
</P>
<P>
He said Mexico is planning to improve its tourism
infrastructure, noting that by the end of 2000, 160 projects, at 6
billion dollars, will be added in 26 of the country's 31 states.
</P>
<P>
These projects will include hotels, restaurants, golf courses
and beach resorts, he added.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala is the third stop of Espinosa's promotional visit in
the tourist corridor dominated by the Maya World in Central
America after Honduras and Belize. His visit will conclude on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Espinosa will attend a ministerial meeting over
the multi-national program of the Maya World in Belize. 
</P>
</TEXT>
