<HEADLINE> Art Market Flourishes in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, China's largest port
city in the north, has witnessed a fast growing market of art
works in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In the 15-year-old Ancient Culture Street in the downtown area,
the 80 art stores and departments reported a total retail revenue
of nearly 24 million yuan in 1998 alone.
</P>
<P>
All around Tianjin are shops selling inscriptions, oil
paintings, porcelain, pottery, jade objects, sculptures and many
other rare articles.
</P>
<P>
Inscriptions and paintings by renowned calligraphers and
artists, and refined art works from other provinces, as well as
jade articles imported from Pakistan, are sold exclusively in many
newly-built stores in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Seven local artists have opened their own studios to paint and
draw pictures according to the demands of the customers.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate the art market and to attract more collectors and
buyers, Tianjin hosts art auctions periodically.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that sustained economic development is the main
reason behind the prosperity of the art market.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's local specialties are new year pictures, red paper-
cuts, painted sculptures and clay figurines.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jianshan, who has run an art works business for many years,
said that though Tianjin has a fine artistic tradition, people
used to prefer to spend their money in restaurants. But now they
are turning to art works.
</P>
<P>
Sun's store is one of the most profitable of such stores in
Tianjin. He said the development of the market is still at the
primary stage, but it will be more flourishing in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
