<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Improves First Aid Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A first-aid network, composed of
a first-aid center, four branches and 13 main hospitals, has been
recently set up in this open coastal city in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Sun Chengdai, head of the city Bureau of Health, said that the
center will first record all the "120" callings for medical help,
and then select the nearest branch for the assignment, ensuring
that emergency patients get first aid within 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 13 main hospitals will take charge of the
hospitalization of the patients, and improve the first-aid service
by simplifying procedures.
</P>
<P>
The first-aid center has 30 ambulances of various kinds,
including ones for special services, such as for patients with
infectious diseases. Three of them have pacemaker
electrotherapeutic apparatus, and 22 have electrocardiographs and
oxygen inhalators.
</P>
<P>
The network will increase the annual first-aid capacity to some
300,000 patients, and hospitalize three million patients in
critical conditions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China as a whole can only offer first-aid
service to less than one percent of emergency patients, and over
70 percent of patients with cardiovascular, cerebral, or
respiratory system diseases die on the way to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Shanghai, and Dalian have been making continuous
efforts for the improvement of first-aid services for the last 20
years, and the newly-established system in Dalian has been
recognized by the Ministry of Health as a model in this regard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rules on Foreign Students Studying in China Mapped Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Education has
drafted a regulation offering guidelines for primary and middle
schools enrolling foreign children who wish to study in China.
</P>
<P>
Primary and middle schools, with approval from provincial-level
education, foreign affairs and public security departments, can
enroll foreign students who are living in China with their parents
on a long-term basis, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Foreign children living temporarily in the country must find
Chinese or resident foreigners to act as their guardians if they
want to enter primary or middle schools in China.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also pointed out that students who intend to
study for over six months in China should submit their visa
applications and school admission notices to Chinese embassies or
consulates to obtain an "X" visa.
</P>
<P>
"They must apply for residence permits from the exit and entry
administrations of local public security departments within 30
days since they enter China," Ministry sources were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Those studying for less than six months must apply for "F"
visas from Chinese embassies or consulates.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign students should live with their parents or guardians.
Well-equipped schools can provide foreign students with
dormitories after they receive approval from the authorities," the
sources told.
</P>
<P>
Regional education and pricing departments will decide how much
the schools should charge the foreign students.
</P>
<P>
Schools will not open extra courses for foreign students,
except for Chinese language classes. Foreign students can take
part in activities organized by the schools, but are exempt from
politics and ethics courses.
</P>
<P>
Students will be granted certificates if they pass appropriate
examinations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
