<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Sports Council Chairman Ready to Take Blame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Sports Council (KONI)
Chairman Wismoyo Arismunandar said he is ready to be held
responsible for the country's failure to become kingpins in the
newly concluded 20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games.
</P>
<P>
"As the highest ranking official in sports, I'm responsible for
what we've accomplished in Brunei," he said during the ceremony
held to commemorate the 54th Indonesian Independence Day here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are indeed disappointed over the result, where for the
first time in over 22 years, we only managed to end in third place.
But, blaming each other and looking for a scapegoat will not do us
any good. Let's accept it brave-heartedly and evaluate what has
gone wrong in the campaign," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia went through a bad spell in Brunei only managing to
amass 44 golds to finish third behind Thailand and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
However, Wismoyo praised the athletes for what they had done in
fulfilling their deeds to the country.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the bad outcome, I think all athletes have given their
best to the country and I thank them for that," he was quoted by
The Indonesian Observer Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had set a target to win at least 60 golds in the
proceedings, but they failed to anticipate the progress made by
rivals and had to settle with the worst scenario of being
surpassed by Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
