</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Not to Use Radar to Monitor DPRK's Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon confirmed
Tuesday that Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
had turned down a U.S. commander's request to use a new
missile-defense radar to monitor possible launch of Taepo Dong
missile by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Confirming a report in Tuesday's Washington Times newspaper,
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters that Shelton had
denied a request from the U.S. Space Command to send the Theater
High-Altitude Area Defense (THAAD) radar temporarily to Japan in
part because of the cost involved.
</P>
<P>
"There are a variety of (intelligence) collection assets that
we will have at sea and in the air. And General Shelton felt that
those were adequate and that the THAAD radar was not going to be
necessary," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
The radar is part of an advanced system designed to be used in
a planned U.S. missile defense. Although the United States would
not use the radar to monitor possible launch of the DPRK's
missile, it was planned for use in the coming months, Bacon said,
but declining to elaborate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Rises 0.7 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve said
Tuesday that industrial output rose 0.7 percent in July, the
biggest increase in four months.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said the 0.7 percent advance in output at factories,
mines and utilities followed lackluster gains of 0.1 percent in
June and 0.2 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output jumped 0.6 percent in July, the strongest
advance since October. Analysts believe that U.S. factories, hard
hit by the loss of export markets, are beginning to recover.
</P>
<P>
The pickup in output, which reflected a weather-related
increase in output at utility plants, pushed the overall operating
rate up to 80.7 percent of capacity in July. This is still far
below the level at which analysts begin to worry about production
bottlenecks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990818.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
