<P>
It was evident from the start of this encounter that both teams
were determined to not only showcase their skills, but entertain
the fans and more so the former South African President, Nelson
Mandela, as the nation bade him farewell.
</P>
<P>
The first 45 minutes was as entertaining as it was revealing,
but the game changed dramatically at the second half. The African
XI broke the ice when South Africa's Phil Masinga swept down the
right flank, cut in and sent in an inviting cross and Zambia's
Kalusha Bwalya scored a brilliant goal in the 51st minute.
</P>
<P>
The African XI barely had enough time to celebrate their lead
as Germany's Thomas Haessler within a minute scored an equalizer
after two beautiful crosses from his World XI colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The World stars gained the upper hand in the 65th minute when
Haessler's pass found Lubomir Moravcik of Slovakia who rifled it
past the African XI's goalkeeper, South Africa's Brian Baloyi.
</P>
<P>
The most dramatic movement came at the end of the game when the
African XI won a free kick in the 92nd minute and Bwalya scored
his second goal.
</P>
<P>
Before the match Mandela shook hands and chatted with the
players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
