<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 17 (Xinhua) -- A late-day rally pushed Wall
Street stocks higher in the third straight session Tuesday as a
consumer prices report raised hope that the Federal Reserve will
take a moderate action in raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 70.29 at 11,117.08.
The blue chip index rose 257.40 points in the two previous
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 13.39 at 1,344.16. The technology heavy
Nasdaq index rose 25.94 at 2,671.22.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied after the Labor Department reported that the
Consumer Price Index rose 0.3 percent in July, indicating little
pressure on inflation. The new data made investors believe that
the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates only modestly.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve raised the short-term interest rates on
June 30 and three weeks later, its chairman Alan Greenspan warned
the market of another rate hike if the new data signaled
inflationary pressures. Greenspan's warning has pushed stocks
lower.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 5.82 at 628.71 and the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.18 at 436.00. But the
American Stock Exchange index fell 1.09 at 778.41.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,844 up, 1,147 down and 542
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 689.88 million shares from 576.97
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
